ghton}}\n| length22 = 2:29\n\n| title23 = Thanx\n| length23 = 5:56\n| writer23 = {{hlist|Parker|Nowell}}\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline        = [[Skunk Records]] compact disc\n| total_length    = 73:48\n\n| title23 = Thanx\n| length23 = 4:23\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline        = [[MCA Records]] version\n| total_length    = 69:15\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n\n| title1 = Waiting for My Ruca\n| length1 = 2:20\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Bradley Nowell]]|[[Eric Wilson (bassist)|Eric Wilson]]|[[Bud Gaugh|Floyd Gaugh]]}}\n| extra1 = Sublime\n\n| title2 = 40oz. to Freedom\n| length2 = 3:02\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Nowell|[[Marshall Goodman]]}}\n| extra2 = Sublime\n\n| title3 = [[Smoke Two Joints]]\n| length3 = 2:53\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Chris Kay|Michael Kay}}\n| extra3 = Miguel\n\n| title4 = [[We're Only Gonna Die for Our Arrogance]]\n| length4 = 3:27\n| writer4 = Greg Graffin\n\n| title5 = Don't Push\n| length5 = 4:18\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Nowell|Goodman}}\n\n| title6 = [[54-46 That's My Number|5446 That's My Number]]/Ball and Chain\n| length6 = 5:17\n| writer6 = [[Toots Hibbert|Frederick Hibbert]]\n\n| title7 = [[Badfish (song)|Badfish]]\n| length7 = 3:04\n| writer7 = Nowell\n| extra7 = Miguel\n\n| title8 = Let's Go Get Stoned\n| length8 = 3:32\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Nowell|Wilson|Gaugh}}\n\n| title9 = New Thrash\n| length9 = 1:30\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Nowell|Goodman}}\n\n| title10 = [[Scarlet Begonias]]\n| length10 = 3:31\n| writer10 = {{hlist|[[Jerry Garcia]]|[[Robert Hunter (lyricist)|Robert Hunter]]}}\n| extra10 = Miguel\n\n| title11 = Live at E's\n| length11 = 3:08\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Nowell|Wilson|Gaugh}}\n\n| title12 = D.J.s\n| length12 = 3:18\n| writer12 = Nowell\n\n| title13 = Chica Me Tipo\n| length13 = 2:16\n| writer13 = {{hlist|Nowell|Wilson|Gaugh}}\n\n| title14 = Right Back\n| length14 = 2:49\n| writer14 = {{hlist|Nowell|Goodman}}\n\n| title15 = What Happened\n| length15 = 3:27\n| writer15 = [[B.B. King]]\n\n| title16 = New Song\n| length16 = 3:14\n| writer16 = {{hlist|Nowell|Wilson|Gaugh}}\n\n| title17 = Ebin\n| length17 = 3:32\n| writer17 = {{hlist|Nowell|Goodman}}\n\n| title18 = [[Date Rape (song)|Date Rape]]\n| length18 = 3:38\n| writer18 = {{hlist|Nowell|Wilson|Gaugh|Goodman}}\n\n| title19 = Hope\n| writer19 = Milo Aukerman\n| length19 = 1:43\n\n| title20 = KRS-One\n| length20 = 2:23\n| writer20 = {{hlist|[[KRS-One|Lawrence Parker]]|Nowell}}\n\n| title21 = [[Rivers of Babylon]]\n| writer21 = {{hlist|Frank Farian|Brent Dowe|George Reyam|Nowell|James McNaughton}}\n| length21 = 2:29\n\n| title22 = Thanx\n| length22 = 5:56\n| writer22 = {{hlist|Parker|Nowell}}\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n'''Sublime'''\n* [[Bradley Nowell]] \u2013 vocals, guitar, and percussion\n* [[Eric Wilson (bassist)|Eric Wilson]] \u2013 bass, vocals (track #12), and xylophone (track #22)\n* [[Bud Gaugh]] \u2013 drums and percussion (tracks #8, #9, #13, and #17)\n\nOther Personnel\n* [[Marshall Goodman]] \u2013 drums (all tracks except #8, #9, #13, and #17), turntables, samples, and vocals (track #12)\n*[[Brian Wallace]] \u2013 baritone saxophone\n*[[Chris Hauser]] \u2013 trumpet\n\n== Production ==\n* Producers: [[Miguel Happoldt|Michael \"Miguel\" Happoldt]], [[Sublime (band)|Sublime]], Elephant Levitation\n* Engineers: Anthony Antoine Arvizu, Steve McNeil\n* Mastering: Brian Gardner\n* Artwork: [[Opie Ortiz]]\n* Photos: Josh Coffman\n\n== Chart positions ==\n\n=== Album ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Album\n!Chart\n!Position\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''40oz. to Freedom''\n| Heatseekers\n| No. 15\n|}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.sublimelbc.com/ Official Sublime website]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{sublimeband}}\n\n[[Category:Skunk Records albums]]\n[[Category:1992 debut albums]]\n[[Category:MCA Records albums]]\n[[Category:Sublime (band) albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = 40oz. to Freedom\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Sublime (band)|Sublime]]\n| cover      = Sublime40OztoFreedomalbumcover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = June 1992\n| recorded   = 1991\u20131992 at Mambo in [[Long Beach, California]]\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Ska punk]], [[reggae rock]]\n| length     = 75:22 (Cassette version)<br />73:48 (Compact Disc version)\n| label      = [[Skunk Records|Skunk]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Sublime (band)|Sublime]]|[[Miguel Happoldt|Miguel]]|Elephant Levitation}}\n| prev_title = Jah Won't Pay the Bills\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[Robbin' the Hood]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n}}\n\n'''''40oz. to Freedom''''' is the [[1992 in music|1992]] debut album by the [[Southern California]] [[ska-punk]] band [[Sublime (band)|Sublime]] released by [[Skunk Records]] and again by [[MCA Records|MCA]]. ''40oz. to Freedom'' received mixed critical reviews upon its first release but has earned an improved public perception since. Sublime would not achieve any mainstream success until the release of [[Sublime (album)|their eponymous album]] in 1996, two months after the death of their lead singer and guitarist, [[Bradley Nowell]]. As of 2011, the album has certified sales of two million copies in the US and is Sublime's second best-selling studio album there (the self-titled album leads with six million). Along with [[The Offspring]]'s 1994 album ''[[Smash (The Offspring album)|Smash]]'', ''40oz. to Freedom'' is one of the highest-selling independently released albums of all time.\n\n''40oz. to Freedom'''s sound blended various forms of [[Music of Jamaica|Jamaican music]], including [[ska]] ([[Date Rape (song)|\"Date Rape\"]]), [[rocksteady]] (\"[[54-46 That's My Number]]\"), [[roots reggae]] (\"[[Smoke Two Joints]]\"), and [[dub music|dub]] (\"Let's Go Get Stoned\", \"D.J.s\") along with British and American [[hardcore punk]] (\"New Thrash\", \"Hope\") and [[hip hop music|hip hop]] (as in \"Live at E's\").\n\n== Background ==\nAt the age of sixteen, [[Bradley Nowell]] began playing guitar and started his first band, Hogan's Heroes, with  Michael Yates and [[Eric Wilson (bassist)|Eric Wilson]], who would later become Sublime's bassist.<ref name=\"Drug Bust\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xGB0iIRXtJEC&lpg=PA64&dq=Sublime%20Bradley%20Nowell&lr&as_pt=MAGAZINES&rview=1&pg=PA63#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Drug Bust: When Brad Nowell Died of a Heroin Overdose|date=1997-01-06|accessdate=2011-02-04|work=Spin|last=Smith|first=RJ}}</ref>  At first, Wilson did not share Nowell's interest in reggae music.  Nowell recalled the experience: \"I was trying to get them to do ([[UB40]]'s version of) 'Cherry Oh Baby', and it didn't work. They tried, but it just sounded like such garbage.  We were horrible.\"<ref name=\"Most\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-05-04/entertainment/ca-62206_1_sublime-songs|title=Sublime Making the Most of '40oz.' of Success|last=Boehm|first=Mike|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Eddy Hartenstein|date=May 4, 1995|accessdate=December 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, music student [[Michael Happoldt|Michael \"Miguel\" Happoldt]] approached the band, offering to let the band record in the studio at the school where Happoldt was studying.  The band enthusiastically agreed and broke into the school at night, where they recorded from midnight to seven in the morning.<ref name=VH1behindthemusic>{{cite episode | title = Sublime|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/behind_the_music/episode.jhtml?episodeID=55758 | series = [[Behind the Music]] | network = [[VH1]] | airdate = May 30, 2001 | accessdate=February 2, 2011}}</ref>  The recording session resulted in the popular cassette tape called ''[[Jah Won't Pay the Bills]]'', which was released in 1991. The tape helped the band gain a grassroots following throughout Southern California.  Using the same tactics implemented for the recording of ''Jah Won't Pay the Bills'', the band recorded ''40oz. to Freedom'' in secrecy at the studios in [[California State University, Dominguez Hills]].<ref name=\"Limit\">{{cite news|title=Ska's the Limit for Controversial Band Sublime|last=Freedom du Lac|first=J.|work=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|publisher=Cheryl Dell|date=November 5, 1995}}</ref>  Nowell recalled \"You weren't supposed to be in there after 9 p.m., but we'd go in at 9:30 and stay until 5 in the morning. We'd just hide from the security guards. They never knew we were there. We managed to get $30,000 worth of studio time for free.\"<ref name=\"Limit\"/>\n\n== Influences ==\nSublime themselves credit a number of local reggae and rap bands from California for inspiration in their Thanx Dub.  In addition to explicit mentions of artists like [[KRS-One]] and [[Half Pint]], Nowell makes copious allusions to others through his lyrics. The line \"Stolen from an Africa land\" in \"Don't Push\", for example, alludes to [[Bob Marley]]'s [[Buffalo Soldier (song)|\"Buffalo Soldier\"]].  References are also made to [[Boomtown Rats]], [[Beastie Boys]], [[Tenor Saw]], [[Pink Floyd]], [[The Specials]], [[The Ziggens]], [[Minutemen (band)|Minutemen]], [[Jimi Hendrix]], [[Just-Ice]], [[Fishbone]], [[Public Enemy (group)|Public Enemy]], and [[Flavor Flav]], among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sublimestp.com/?page=pages/40ozwis#3 |title=sublime STP |publisher=sublime STP |date= |accessdate=2011-03-15}}</ref>\n\nThe album has six covers: \n* \"[[Smoke Two Joints]]\" (by [[The Toyes]])\n* \"[[We're Only Gonna Die]]\" (by [[Bad Religion]])\n* \"[[54-46 That's My Number]]\" (by [[Toots & the Maytals]])\n* \"[[Scarlet Begonias]]\" (by [[Grateful Dead]])\n* \"[[Rivers of Babylon]]\" (by [[The Melodians]])\n* \"[[Milo Goes to College|Hope]]\" (by the [[Descendents (band)|Descendents]])\n\nThe song \"Don't Push\" contains lyrics from the [[Beastie Boys]] song \"[[Looking Down the Barrel of a Gun]]\". \nThe song \"D.J.s\" contains a lyric from Bob Marley's \"Ride Natty Ride\" with \"Dred gotta a job to do\". The song \"D.J.s\" closes with lyrics from the [[Dandy Livingstone]] song \"[[Rudy, A Message to You]]\" which was popularized by [[The Specials]], another band often credited as a Sublime influence. \nIn \"New Thrash,\" the words \"There ain't no life nowhere\" can be heard in the background, a reference to the [[Jimi Hendrix Experience]] song \"I Don't Live Today\" where the same words can be heard. \n\"New Song\" starts the same as the 1990 song 'The Nigga Ya Love To Hate' by [[Ice Cube]], with the line \"I heard payback's a motherfuckin\".\n\n== Release history ==\n\nThe album was originally released by [[Skunk Records]] on compact disc and cassette. The original cassette version contained a longer version of the track \"Thanx\"; the cassette version was 5:56, while the length was 4:23 on all other releases of the album. A longer instrumental version of the recording appears on the compilation ''[[Second-hand Smoke]]'' as \"Thanx [[Dub music|Dub]]\", with a length of 6:28.\n\nThe album was reissued by Gasoline Alley Records and [[MCA Records|MCA]] with a different track listing, removing the song \"Get Out!\" and the hidden track \"[[Rawhide (song)|Rawhide]]\" due to copyright issues \u2014 \"Get Out!\" contained unlicensed samples, and \"Rawhide\", which appeared at the end of \"[[Date Rape (song)|Date Rape]]\", was an uncredited cover of the theme to the [[Rawhide (TV series)|TV series of the same name]]. However, in the album booklet, the lyrics for \"Get Out!\" are still printed. Additionally, other unlicensed samples were removed from the songs \"We're Only Gonna Die for Our Arrogance\" and \"Let's Go Get Stoned\".\n\nThe reedited version was released as a picture disc limited edition vinyl album in 2002, following the sixth anniversary of the events of 1996. A limited edition vinyl was released through Hot Topic in 2010.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r229208/review|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic Review]</ref>\n|rev2 = Punknews.org\n|rev2score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>[http://www.punknews.org/review/270 Punknews.org Review]</ref>\n|rev3 = [[Pitchfork Media]]\n|rev3score = 5.6/10<ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite news |last1=Rytlewski |first1=Evan |title=Sublime: 40oz. to Freedom Album Review |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/sublime-40oz-to-freedom/ |accessdate=30 April 2019 |work=Pitchfork}}</ref>\n| noprose = yes\n| rev4 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"Cross\">{{cite book|last=Cross|first=Charles R.|authorlink=Charles R. Cross|editor1-last=Brackett|editor1-first=Nathan|editor2-last=Hoard|editor2-first=Christian|title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|edition=4th|year=2004|isbn=0-7432-0169-8|chapter=Sublime|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/790 790]}}</ref>\n}}\n[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] gave the album a mixed review, acknowledging its influence while also critiquing the band for attempting to include too many contradictory styles and influences at once, creating an incoherent sound, saying, \"The debut album from the SoCal trio is a flawed artifact of \u201990s alt-rock, punk, ska, and hip-hop, but remains a fascinating document of Bradley Nowell as the honey-voiced musical tourist bro.\"<ref name=\"pitchfork\"/>\n\nThe author of the article also called the album \"prescient\" in foreshadowing the role hip-hop would have on late 90's rock, adding that much of the influence of the album was the lifestyle captured in the lyrics, adding, \"the album resonated because it captured a lifestyle. Rejecting the smoldering angst of the grunge music that was beginning to take root on the radio, Sublime made revelry their primary muse, detailing parties, hookups, and bad decisions with such rowdy immediacy.\"  The article also remarks that \"time hasn't flattered\" the album due to the lyrical content concerning consent and treatment of women.<ref name=\"pitchfork\"/>\n\n===Legacy===\nRemembering the album on the 25th anniversary of its release, ''LA Weekly'' wrote, \"If ''40oz. to Freedom'' revels in its careening, narcotic whimsy, that's partially why it's stood the test of time. At its core, music is utilitarian, and Sublime reached a universality of experience that can't become obsolete.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.laweekly.com/music/sublimes-40oz-to-freedom-is-a-long-beach-classic-haters-be-damned-8489130 | title = The Haters Are Wrong: Sublime's 40oz. to Freedom Is a Long Beach Classic | date = 2 August 2017 | accessdate = 18 April 2017 | newspaper = LA Weekly | author = Jeff Weiss }}</ref>\n\n===Commercial performance===\nSince its release in 1992, the album has proved to be a seller over time, moving over two million copies in the US alone and being certified Multi Platinum by the RIAA.<ref>[https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH RIAA \u2013 Gold & Platinum] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626000000/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |date=June 26, 2007 }} (type in \"Sublime\" in the artist box)</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll tracks produced by [[Sublime (band)|Sublime]] and Elephant Levitation, except where noted. Track listing adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Try the TIDAL Web Player |url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/62096206 |website=listen.tidal.com |accessdate=15 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = no\n| headline        = [[Skunk Records]] cassette version\n| total_length    = 75:22\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n\n| title1 = Waiting for My Ruca\n| length1 = 2:20\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Bradley Nowell]]|[[Eric Wilson (bassist)|Eric Wilson]]|[[Bud Gaugh|Floyd Gaugh]]}}\n| extra1 = Sublime\n\n| title2 = Get Out!\n| length2 = 3:32\n\n| title3 = 40oz. to Freedom\n| length3 = 3:02\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Nowell|[[Marshall Goodman]]}}\n| extra3 = Sublime\n\n| title4 = [[Smoke Two Joints]]\n| length4 = 2:53\n| write