date = 1758 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=O9jVCfde0ScC&source=gbs_navlinks_s | ref=harv | author-mask=3}}\n* {{cite book | last = Edwards | first = Jonathan | author-link = Jonathan Edwards (theologian) | title = Edwards on Revivals: Containing A Faithful Narrative of the Surprising Work of God in the Conversion of Many Hundred Souls in Northhampton, Massachusetts, A.D. 1735 : Also Thoughts on the Revival of Religion in New England, 1742, and the Way in which it Ought to be Acknowledged and Promoted | date = 1832 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=O9jVCfde0ScC&source=gbs_navlinks_s | ref=harv | author-mask=3}}\n\n[[Category:Calvinist theology]]\n[[Category:History of Christianity in the United States]]\n[[Category:19th-century Calvinism]]\n[[Category:Congregationalism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Evangelicalism in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ltwin", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEdwards's theology:Wikilinks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_England_theology"}
{"title_page": "AVX Corporation", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name  = AVX Corporation\n| logo  = AVX Corporation Logo.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| type  = [[Public company|Public]] \n| traded_as  = {{NYSE|AVX}}<br>[[Russell 2000 Index|Russell 2000 Component]]\n| genre  =  \n| foundation  = 1972<!-- this parameter modifies \"Founded\" -->\n| founder  =  \n| location_city  = [[Greenville, SC]]\n| location_country  = United States\n| key_people  = John Sarvis ([[CEO]]) <br> John Lawing ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]]) <br> Kurt P. Cummings ([[CFO]])\n| industry  = [[electronics]]\n| products  = [[capacitor]]s, [[Electrical connectors|electr connectors]]<br>[[electronic component]]s [[Ceramic capacitor]]s<br>[[varistor]]s, [[thermistor]]s<br>EMI Filters\n| revenue  = $1,312.661 mil [[Fiscal Year|fy 2017]]{{increase}}9.8%<ref name=tenreport>{{cite web|url=http://investorrelations.avx.com/sites/avx.investorhq.businesswire.com/files/doc_library/file/FY17_10-K.pdf|title=AVX Corp 2017 fiscal year SEC 10-K report|date=2010-06-09}}</ref>\n| net_income  = $125.785 mil [[Fiscal Year|fy 2017]]{{increase}}23.8%<ref name=tenreport/>\n| operating_income  = \n| assets  = $2,477.413 mil {{increase}}2.8%<ref name=tenreport/>\n| equity  = \n| divisions  = Passive Components<br>KED Resale<br>AVX Interconnect (a.k.a. Elco)\n| num_employees  = 10,800 (March'17)\n| homepage  =  {{URL|http://www.avx.com}}\n}}\n'''AVX Corporation''', is an American manufacturer of [[electronic component]]s headquartered in [[Fountain Inn, South Carolina]]. It is the largest industrial employer in [[Horry County, South Carolina]], with almost 1000 workers in [[Myrtle Beach, South Carolina|Myrtle Beach]] and [[Conway, South Carolina|Conway]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesunnews.com/155/story/1198311.html|title=Myrtle Beach economy takes hit with AVX move|first1=Adva|last1=Saldinger|first2=Claudia|last2=Lauer|first3=Monique|last3=Newton|work=[[The Sun News]]|date=2009-12-04|accessdate=2009-12-09}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> AVX has 9,900 employees and operates in the United States, [[Europe]] and [[Asia]]. AVX is a subsidiary of [[Kyocera|Kyocera Electronics Corporation]].\n<ref name=hoover>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoovers.com/company/AVX_Corporation/ccfxyi-1.html?PAGE=1|title=AVX Corporation - Company Profile from Hoover's|accessdate=2009-12-09}}</ref>\n\n2012 sales were $1.545 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corporateinformation.com/Company-Snapshot.aspx?cusip=002444107 |title=AVX Corporation (AVX) Company Profile |publisher=corporateinformation.com |accessdate=2009-12-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717141009/http://www.corporateinformation.com/Company-Snapshot.aspx?cusip=002444107 |archivedate=2011-07-17 }}</ref>  Capital expenditure for the year 2010 was at a five-year low of $28.888 million 34.6% lower than the year before and sixty percent less than in 2008, earnings per share grew 78.7% even though total sales fell (although revenue grew with each successive quarter since April 2009)<ref name=tenreport/>\n\n==Products==\nAVX has three business units. Passive Components includes electrical components for [[Vehicle brake|automotive braking]], [[cell phone]]s, [[copier]]s, [[hearing aid]]s, and [[locomotive]]s. KED Resale sells Kyocera products including [[Ceramic capacitor|ceramic]] and [[tantalum capacitor]]s. [[Electrical connectors|Connectors]] are used in the [[Automotive industry|automotive]] and [[Medicine|medical]] industries.<ref>[https://www.fclane.com/news/understanding-different-connector-brands-we-stock Understanding The Different Connector Brands That We Stock]</ref>\n\nMajor customers of AVX include [[Motorola]], [[Nokia]] and [[Robert Bosch GmbH]].\n\nAsia accounts for 45 percent of AVX sales.<ref name=hoover/>\n\n==History==\nAVX began in 1972 making ceramic capacitors as a subsidiary of Aerovox Corporation, a company founded in 1922 as Radiola Wireless Corporation, which made radios. In June 1973, AVX became the parent company when assets of Aerovox were sold. That same year, Marshall D. Butler, who played a major role in the company's growth, became chairman and [[CEO]].\n\nButler cofounded Alloys Unlimited Inc. in 1957, which was sold to London-based [[Plessey|Plessey Co.]] in 1970; Butler stayed for several years as president of the Plessey subsidiary. With his experience in the [[semiconductor]] field, Butler decided AVX should emphasize multilayer ceramic capacitors (MLCCs), used in the rapidly expanding [[integrated circuit]] field. Butler sold two other divisions and started a five-year plan. The company's $20 million investment and careful analysis of the market resulted in 1979 sales of $95 million and dominance of the market; the goal, based on 30 percent annual growth, had been $83 million.\n\nAVX added operations in Europe, but moving into Japan proved more difficult because of Japan's protected home market. The company's license would not let it sell in Japan, but Kyocera Corporation could sell its products in the United States. Kyocera CEO Kazuo Inamori agreed with Butler that the situation needed to be changed, and Kyocera ended the unfair provision. In 1979 AVX started a Japanese subsidiary.\n\nDuring the 1980s, growth continued, with 1984 sales reaching $234 million. But that year, it became clear that [[computer]] manufacturers had bought more capacitors than needed, and a slowdown began in the industry. AVX continued to grow through new product research and buying other companies. By the end of the decade sales reached $450 million.\n\nIn the late 1980s, the European operations of AVX represented one-fourth of sales. AVX wanted to manufacture parts for Kyocera, which had only 2 percent of its sales in Europe and hoped to increase that before the [[European Community]] made that more difficult. Inamori wanted to buy AVX rather than partner with the company. After a $267 million [[stock]] purchase, AVX has operated as part of Kyocera Corp. since January 18, 1990.\n\nButler retired as CEO in 1993 but remained on the [[board of directors]]. Benedict P. Rosen, an employee since the company's start, became the new CEO. By 1995, sales reached almost $1 billion after significant growth for [[personal computer]]s and cell phones. At the same time, the automotive, [[home appliance]] and medical industries needed electronic components, and advanced electronic systems needed capacitors as well. AVX also sold Kyocera products worldwide and helped the company start operations in Mexico and [[Indonesia]]. Kyocera helped AVX start manufacturing connectors.\n\nIn 1995, Kyocera sold one-fourth of AVX for $557 million, which more than returned the company's investment in AVX, even though Kyocera still owned three-fourths of the company. AVX used the money to enter the connector business and increase its manufacturing of ceramic and tantalum capacitors.\n\nThe boom in the capacitor industry once again proved temporary, after customers bought more products than they needed. But in 1998, personal computers and cell phones contributed to more growth, as did newer electronics in cars. At the same time, material prices went up, and an [[1997 Asian Financial Crisis|Asian currency crisis]] added to AVX's troubles. Layoffs resulted, but by 2000 the company was doing well again, adding operations in [[El Salvador]] and the [[Czech Republic]] (Lan\u0161kroun).\n\nBy the end of fiscal 2001, AVX had 26 plants in 12 countries, 21,000 employees, and sales of $2.6 billion. But a [[Early 2000s recession|recession]] put an end to the good times, and revenues dropped to $1.25 billion; employee numbers totalled 12,500. Production moved to the Czech Republic in the late 1990s and China from 2005 onwards.\n\nThe industry situation appeared to improve by 2004, though AVX still lost money.<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/AVX-Corporation-Company-History.html|title=AVX Corporation - Company History|publisher=fundinguniverse.com|accessdate=2009-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/q/pr?s=AVX|title=AVX: Profile for A V X CORP|publisher=Yahoo! Finance|accessdate=2009-12-09}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2009 the company decided to close a number of its smaller worldwide factories including its flagship manufacturing plant in [[Paignton, UK]] following the credit crunch in an effort to reduce costs and remain financially viable for shareholders.\n\nOn December 3, 2009, AVX announced it would move corporate headquarters to [[Greenville, South Carolina]], with about 150 jobs leaving the Myrtle Beach area. The company planned no change to manufacturing in Conway and Myrtle Beach.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/AVX-Corporation-Announces-bw-930337009.html?x=0&.v=1 |title=AVX Corporation Announces Relocation of Corporate Offices |work=Yahoo! Finance |date=2009-12-03 |accessdate=2009-12-09 }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, AVX announced plans to tear down the original Myrtle Beach plant built in 1949 and updated in 1985, with manufacturing operations continuing at a nearby location on the same land.<ref name=Delay>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/11/03/2480035/avx-demolition-plans-delay-pollution.html\n |title=AVX demolition plans delay pollution cleanup proposal in Myrtle Beach \n |last=Wren \n |first=David \n |work=[[The Sun News]] \n |date=2011-11-03 \n |accessdate=2011-11-03 \n}}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The demolition took place in 2015.<ref name=Perry/>\n\n==Litigation==\nIn 2007, Myrtle Beach property owners near the AVX plant filed suit, claiming [[trichloroethylene]] (TCE) used at the plant until the 1980s has polluted their neighborhood and lowered property values. Another lawsuit claimed the pollution had stopped a [[condominium]] development in the area. A consultant for one of the land owners, Horry Land Co., discovered the pollution in 2006 while doing environmental testing prior to development of a portion of the land. In 2009, AVX claimed [[Myrtle Beach Air Force Base]] caused at least part of the pollution, and the company added the [[United States Air Force|air force]] to one of several lawsuits. A geologist for AVX claims the pollution could be cleaned up in five years and Horry Land is not entitled to compensation, while the consultant for Horry Land claims there is no way to tell how long cleanup will take, since AVX has been trying to clean up its own pollution for 28 years.<ref name=Wren>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesunnews.com/2010/02/23/1331349/avx-loses-bid-to-avoid-court.html |title=AVX loses bid to avoid court |last=Wren |first=David |work=[[The Sun News]] |date=2010-02-23 |accessdate=2010-02-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006162135/http://www.thesunnews.com/2010/02/23/1331349/avx-loses-bid-to-avoid-court.html |archivedate=2011-10-06 }}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2010, federal judge Terry Wooten ruled that evidence in the Horry Land suit showed the plaintiffs were entitled to a trial.<ref name=Wren/> On February 23, 2011, the trial began in [[Florence, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/02/26/2004376/experts-testify-in-avx-case.html \n |title=Experts testify in AVX case; Geologists discuss water pollution in Myrtle Beach \n |last=Wren \n |first=David \n |work=[[The Sun News]] \n |date=2011-02-26 \n |accessdate=2011-02-26 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717035748/http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/02/26/2004376/experts-testify-in-avx-case.html \n |archivedate=2011-07-17 \n}}</ref> In May 2011, Wooten ruled that AVX caused the pollution, and county property records show that AVX purchased 21.5 acres of contaminated land for $4.6 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/05/24/2177112/avx-buys-fouled-land.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120913231116/http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/05/24/2177112/avx-buys-fouled-land.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-09-13|title=AVX buys fouled land in Myrtle Beach|last=Wren|first=David|work=The Sun News|date=2011-05-24|accessdate=2011-05-24}}</ref><ref name=Agree/>\n\nAVX appealed Wooten's 2011 decision on whether the air force should help with the cost of cleanup. [[South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control|S.C. DHEC]] stated in a March 13, 2012 letter that pollution in some areas came from AVX, but in one area another source was responsible. AVX argues that the government's expert, who said groundwater from the base flowed away from the polluted areas, was not qualified to testify about groundwater.  The findings could influence an upcoming [[class-action lawsuit]] by property owners.<ref>{{cite news|first=David|last=Wren|title=State agency says AVX responsible for some \u2013 but not all \u2013 pollution in south Myrtle Beach|work=The Sun News|date=2012-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2012/04/17/2779386/us-government-avx-has-no-basis.html |title=U.S. government: AVX has no basis for pollution appeal |first=David |last=Wren |work=The Sun News |date=2012-04-17 |accessdate=2012-04-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420041243/http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2012/04/17/2779386/us-government-avx-has-no-basis.html |archivedate=2012-04-20 }}</ref>\n\nOn Oct. 25, 2012, ''[[The Sun News]]'' reported that a panel of federal appeals court judges had indicated that they would not overturn a lower court's ruling, thereby granting the electronics components manufacturer a new trial on its groundwater contamination case. AVX claimed that U.S. District Court Judge Terry Wooten made a legal error in its 2011 trial by allowing an unqualified expert witness to testify.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wren |first=David |title=Federal judges question validity of AVX appeal in Myrtle Beach contamination case |url=http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2012/10/25/3135126/federal-judges-question-validity.html |accessdate=2012-10-25 |newspaper=The Sun News |date=2012-10-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028184945/http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2012/10/25/3135126/federal-judges-question-validity.html |archivedate=2012-10-28 }}</ref>\n\nOn July 22, 2013, a jury was selected for the second of three lawsuits regarding pollution on land owned by JDS Development of Myrtle Beach LLC, which asked for damages and lost income from condominiums that were never built. AVX counters that the [[Great Recession in the United States|economic downturn]] caused the failure of the Southern Pines project, and blames the air force for part of the pollution. The suit was filed in 2008 and the trial was scheduled for 2012, but insufficient jurors led to a delay.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wren |first=David |title=Jury selected for Myrtle Beach groundwater pollution trial |url=http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2013/07/22/3599285/jury-selected-for-myrtle-beach.html |accessdate=2013-07-23 |newspaper=The Sun News |date=2013-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054442/http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2013/07/22/3599285/jury-selected-for-myrtle-beach.html |archivedate=2013-09-21 }}</ref> The jury awarded $500,000 in actual damages and $250,000 in punitive damages to JDS, but AVX wanted that amount reduced to no more than $397,500, claiming JDS did not provide \"expert testimony\" to support its views, or evidence Southern Pines would have been a success.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wren|first=David|title=AVX wants judge to eliminate jury\u2019s award in Myrtle Beach pollution case|newspaper=The Sun News|date=2013-08-15}}</ref>\n\nOn October 8, 2014, it was announced that AVX agreed to pay $1.2 million to the owners of 42 properties with TCE contamination. Property owners still needed to approve the settlement, which attorney Gene Connell called \"reasonable.\" The agreement would mean the dismissal of a class-action suit filed nearly seven years earlier.<ref name=Agree>{{cite news|last=Wren |first=David |title=AVX Corp. agrees to pay property owners $1.2 million to settle groundwater pollution lawsuit in Myrtle Beach |url=http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2014/10/08/4525961_avx-corp-agrees-to-pay-property.html?sp=/99/209/&rh=1 |work=The Sun News |date=2014-10-08 |accessdate=2014-10-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016042633/http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2014/10/08/4525961_avx-corp-agrees-to-pay-property.html?sp=%2F99%2F209%2F&rh=1 |archivedate=2014-10-16 }}</ref>\n\nDocuments filed August 5, 2015 show that property owners could sue AVX after a majority of the S.C. Supreme Court reversed a decision by Circuit Court Judge Benjamin Culbertson to dismiss their case. The ruling allows the determination of whether the facts of the case will result in a \"stigma damages\" policy.<ref name=Perry>{{cite news|last=Perry|first1=Charles D.|title=SC Supreme Court clears way for residents\u2019 lawsuit against AVX |url=http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/news/local/article30180396.html|work=[[The Sun News]]|date=2015-08-05|accessdate=2015-08-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.avx.com/ Company website]\n\n{{Kyocera}}\n\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Kyocera]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Greenville, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies established in 1972]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1972]]\n[[Category:Capacitor manufacturers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name  = AVX Corporation\n| logo  = AVX Corporation Logo.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| type  = [[Public company|Public]] \n| traded_as  = {{NYSE|AVX}}<br>[[Russell 2000 Index|Russell 2000 Component]]\n| genre  =  \n| foundation  = 1972<!-- this parameter modifies \"Founded\" -->\n| founder  =  \n| location_city  = [[Greenville, SC]]\n| location_country  = United States\n| key_people  = John Sarvis ([[CEO]]) <br> John Lawing ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]]) <br> Kurt P. Cummings ([[CFO]])\n| industry  = [[electronics]]\n| products  = [[capacitor]]s, [[Electrical connectors|electr connectors]]<br>[[electronic component]]s [[Ceramic capacitor]]s<br>[[varistor]]s, [[thermistor]]s<br>EMI Filters\n| revenue  = $1,312.661 mil [[Fiscal Year|fy 2017]]{{increase}}9.8%<ref name=tenreport>{{cite web|url=http://investorrelations.avx.com/sites/avx.investorhq.businesswire.com/files/doc_library/file/FY17_10-K.pdf|title=AVX Corp 2017 fiscal year SEC 10-K report|date=2010-06-09}}</ref>\n| net_income  = $125.785 mil [[Fiscal Year|fy 2017]]{{increase}}23.8%<ref name=tenreport/>\n| operating_income  = \n| assets  = $2,477.413 mil {{increase}}2.8%<ref name=tenreport/>\n| equity  = \n| divisions  = Passive Components<br>KED Resale<br>AVX Interconnect (a.k.a. Elco)\n| num_employees  = 10,800 (March'17)\n| homepage  =  {{URL|http://www.avx.com}}\n}}\n'''AVX Corporation''', is an American manufacturer of [[electronic component]]s headquartered in [[Fountain Inn, South Carolina]]. It is the largest industrial employer in [[Horry County, South Carolina]], with almost 1000 workers in [[Myrtle Beach, South Carolina|Myrtle Beach]] and [[Conway, South Carolina|Conway]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesunnews.com/155/story/1198311.html|title=Myrtle Beach economy takes hit with AVX move|first1=Adva|last1=Saldinger|first2=Claudia|last2=Lauer|first3=Monique|last3=Newton|work=[[The Sun News]]|date=2009-12-04|accessdate=2009-12-09}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> AVX has 9,900 employees and operates in the United States, [[Europe]] and [[Asia]]. AVX is a subsidiary of [[Kyocera|Kyocera Electronics Corporation]].\n<ref name=hoover>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoovers.com/company/AVX_Corporation/ccfxyi-1.html?PAGE=1|title=AVX Corporation - Company Profile from Hoover's|accessdate=2009-12-09}}</ref>\n\n2012 sales were $1.545 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corporateinformation.com/Company-Snapshot.aspx?cusip=002444107 |title=AVX Corporation (AVX) Company Profile |publisher=corporateinformation.com |accessdate=2009-12-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717141009/http://www.corporateinformation.com/Company-Snapshot.aspx?cusip=002444107 |archivedate=2011-07-17 }}</ref>  Capital expenditure for the year 2010 was at a five-year low of $28.888 million 34.6% lower than the year before and sixty percent less than in 2008, earnings per share grew 78.7% even though total sales fell (although revenue grew with each successive quarter since April 2009)<ref name=tenreport/>\n\n==Products==\nAVX has three business units. Passive Components includes electrical components for [[Vehicle brake|automotive braking]], [[cell phone]]s, [[copier]]s, [[hearing aid]]s, and [[locomotive]]s. KED Resale sells Kyocera products including [[Ceramic capacitor|ceramic]] and [[tantalum capacitor]]s. [[Electrical connectors|Connectors]] are used in the [[Automotive industry|automotive]] and [[Medicine|medical]] industries.<ref>[https://www.fclane.com/news/understanding-different-connector-brands-we-stock Understanding The Different Connector Brands That We Stock]</ref>\n\nMajor customers of AVX include [[Motorola]], [[Nokia]] and [[Robert Bosch GmbH]].\n\nAsia accounts for 45 percent of AVX sales.<ref name=hoover/>\n\n==History==\nAVX began in 1972 making ceramic capacitors as a subsidiary of Aerovox Corporation, a company founded in 1922 as Radiola Wireless Corporation, which made radios. In June 1973, AVX became the parent company when assets of Aerovox were sold. That same year, Marshall D. Butler, who played a major role in the company's growth, became chairman and [[CEO]].\n\nButler cofounded Alloys Unlimited Inc. in 1957, which was sold to London-based [[Plessey|Plessey Co.]] in 1970; Butler stayed for several years as president of the Plessey subsidiary. With his experience in the [[semiconductor]] field, Butler decided AVX should emphasize multilayer ceramic capacitors (MLCCs), used in the rapidly expanding [[integrated circuit]] field. Butler sold two other divisions and started a five-year plan. The company's $20 million investment and careful analysis of the market resulted in 1979 sales of $95 million and dominance of the market; the goal, based on 30 percent annual growth, had been $83 million.\n\nAVX added operations in Europe, but moving into Japan proved more difficult because of Japan's protected home market. The company's license would not let it sell in Japan, but Kyocera Corporation could sell its products in the United States. Kyocera CEO Kazuo Inamori agreed with Butler that the situation needed to be changed, and Kyocera ended the unfair provision. In 1979 AVX started a Japanese subsidiary.\n\nDuring the 1980s, growth continued, with 1984 sales reaching $234 million. But that year, it became clear that [[computer]] manufacturers had bought more capacitors than needed, and a slowdown began in the industry. AVX continued to grow through new product research and buying other companies. By the end of the decade sales reached $450 million.\n\nIn the late 1980s, the European operations of AVX represented one-fourth of sales. AVX wanted to manufacture parts for Kyocera, which had only 2 percent of its sales in Europe and hoped to increase that before the [[European Community]] made that more difficult. Inamori wanted to buy AVX rather than partner with the company. After a $267 million [[stock]] purchase, AVX has operated as part of Kyocera Corp. since January 18, 1990.\n\nButler retired as CEO in 1993 but remained on the [[board of directors]]. Benedict P. Rosen, an employee since the company's start, became the new CEO. By 1995, sales reached almost $1 billion after significant growth for [[personal computer]]s and cell phones. At the same time, the automotive, [[home appliance]] and medical industries needed electronic components, and advanced electronic systems needed capacitors as well. AVX also sold Kyocera products worldwide and helped the company start operations in Mexico and [[Indonesia]]. Kyocera helped AVX start manufacturing connectors.\n\nIn 1995, Kyocera sold one-fourth of AVX for $557 million, which more than returned the company's investment in AVX, even though Kyocera still owned three-fourths of the company. AVX used the money to enter the connector business and increase its manufacturing of ceramic and tantalum capacitors.\n\nThe boom in the capacitor industry once again proved temporary, after customers bought more products than they needed. But in 1998, personal computers and cell phones contributed to more growth, as did newer electronics in cars. At the same time, material prices went up, and an [[1997 Asian Financial Crisis|Asian currency crisis]] added to AVX's troubles. Layoffs resulted, but by 2000 the company was doing well again, adding operations in [[El Salvador]] and the [[Czech Republic]] (Lan\u0161kroun).\n\nBy the end of fiscal 2001, AVX had 26 plants in 12 countries, 21,000 employees, and sales of $2.6 billion. But a [[Early 2000s recession|recession]] put an end to the good times, and revenues dropped to $1.25 billion; employee numbers totalled 12,500. Production moved to the Czech Republic in the late 90's and China from 2005 onwards.\n\nThe industry situation appeared to improve by 2004, though AVX still lost money.<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/AVX-Corporation-Company-History.html|title=AVX Corporation - Company History|publisher=fundinguniverse.com|accessdate=2009-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/q/pr?s=AVX|title=AVX: Profile for A V X CORP|publisher=Yahoo! Finance|accessdate=2009-12-09}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2009 the company decided to close a number of its smaller worldwide factories including its flagship manufacturing plant in [[Paignton, UK]] following the credit crunch in an effort to reduce costs and remain financially viable for shareholders.\n\nOn December 3, 2009, AVX announced it would move corporate headquarters to [[Greenville, South Carolina]], with about 150 jobs leaving the Myrtle Beach area. The company planned no change to manufacturing in Conway and Myrtle Beach.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/AVX-Corporation-Announces-bw-930337009.html?x=0&.v=1 |title=AVX Corporation Announces Relocation of Corporate Offices |work=Yahoo! Finance |date=2009-12-03 |accessdate=2009-12-09 }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, AVX announced plans to tear down the original Myrtle Beach plant built in 1949 and updated in 1985, with manufacturing operations continuing at a nearby location on the same land.<ref name=Delay>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/11/03/2480035/avx-demolition-plans-delay-pollution.html\n |title=AVX demolition plans delay pollution cleanup proposal in Myrtle Beach \n |last=Wren \n |first=David \n |work=[[The Sun News]] \n |date=2011-11-03 \n |accessdate=2011-11-03 \n}}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The demolition took place in 2015.<ref name=Perry/>\n\n==Litigation==\nIn 2007, Myrtle Beach property owners near the AVX plant filed suit, claiming [[trichloroethylene]] (TCE) used at the plant until the 1980s has polluted their neighborhood and lowered property values. Another lawsuit claimed the pollution had stopped a [[condominium]] development in the area. A consultant for one of the land owners, Horry Land Co., discovered the pollution in 2006 while doing environmental testing prior to development of a portion of the land. In 2009, AVX claimed [[Myrtle Beach Air Force Base]] caused at least part of the pollution, and the company added the [[United States Air Force|air force]] to one of several lawsuits. A geologist for AVX claims the pollution could be cleaned up in five years and Horry Land is not entitled to compensation, while the consultant for Horry Land claims there is no way to tell how long cleanup will take, since AVX has been trying to clean up its own pollution for 28 years.<ref name=Wren>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesunnews.com/2010/02/23/1331349/avx-loses-bid-to-avoid-court.html |title=AVX loses bid to avoid court |last=Wren |first=David |work=[[The Sun News]] |date=2010-02-23 |accessdate=2010-02-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006162135/http://www.thesunnews.com/2010/02/23/1331349/avx-loses-bid-to-avoid-court.html |archivedate=2011-10-06 }}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2010, federal judge Terry Wooten ruled that evidence in the Horry Land suit showed the plaintiffs were entitled to a trial.<ref name=Wren/> On February 23, 2011, the trial began in [[Florence, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/02/26/2004376/experts-testify-in-avx-case.html \n |title=Experts testify in AVX case; Geologists discuss water pollution in Myrtle Beach \n |last=Wren \n |first=David \n |work=[[The Sun News]] \n |date=2011-02-26 \n |accessdate=2011-02-26 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717035748/http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/02/26/2004376/experts-testify-in-avx-case.html \n |archivedate=2011-07-17 \n}}</ref> In May 2011, Wooten ruled that AVX caused the pollution, and county property records show that AVX purchased 21.5 acres of contaminated land for $4.6 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/05/24/2177112/avx-buys-fouled-land.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120913231116/http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/05/24/2177112/avx-buys-fouled-land.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-09-13|title=AVX buys fouled land in Myrtle Beach|last=Wren|first=David|work=The Sun News|date=2011-05-24|accessdate=2011-05-24}}</ref><ref name=Agree/>\n\nAVX appealed Wooten's 2011 decision on whether the air force should help with the cost of cleanup. [[South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control|S.C. DHEC]] stated in a March 13, 2012 letter that pollution in some areas came from AVX, but in one area another source was responsible. AVX argues that the government's expert, who said groundwater from the base flowed away from the polluted areas, was not qualified to testify about groundwater.  The findings could influence an upcoming [[class-action lawsuit]] by property owners.<ref>{{cite news|first=David|last=Wren|title=State agency says AVX responsible for some \u2013 but not all \u2013 pollution in south Myrtle Beach|work=The Sun News|date=2012-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2012/04/17/2779386/us-government-avx-has-no-basis.html |title=U.S. government: AVX has no basis for pollution appeal |first=David |last=Wren |work=The Sun News |date=2012-04-17 |accessdate=2012-04-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420041243/http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2012/04/17/2779386/us-government-avx-has-no-basis.html |archivedate=2012-04-20 }}</ref>\n\nOn Oct. 25, 2012, ''[[The Sun News]]'' reported that a panel of federal appeals court judges had indicated that they would not overturn a lower court's ruling, thereby granting the electronics components manufacturer a new trial on its groundwater contamination case. AVX claimed that U.S. District Court Judge Terry Wooten made a legal error in its 2011 trial by allowing an unqualified expert witness to testify.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wren |first=David |title=Federal judges question validity of AVX appeal in Myrtle Beach contamination case |url=http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2012/10/25/3135126/federal-judges-question-validity.html |accessdate=2012-10-25 |newspaper=The Sun News |date=2012-10-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028184945/http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2012/10/25/3135126/federal-judges-question-validity.html |archivedate=2012-10-28 }}</ref>\n\nOn July 22, 2013, a jury was selected for the second of three lawsuits regarding pollution on land owned by JDS Development of Myrtle Beach LLC, which asked for damages and lost income from condominiums that were never built. AVX counters that the [[Great Recession in the United States|economic downturn]] caused the failure of the Southern Pines project, and blames the air force for part of the pollution. The suit was filed in 2008 and the trial was scheduled for 2012, but insufficient jurors led to a delay.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wren |first=David |title=Jury selected for Myrtle Beach groundwater pollution trial |url=http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2013/07/22/3599285/jury-selected-for-myrtle-beach.html |accessdate=2013-07-23 |newspaper=The Sun News |date=2013-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054442/http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2013/07/22/3599285/jury-selected-for-myrtle-beach.html |archivedate=2013-09-21 }}</ref> The jury awarded $500,000 in actual damages and $250,000 in punitive damages to JDS, but AVX wanted that amount reduced to no more than $397,500, claiming JDS did not provide \"expert testimony\" to support its views, or evidence Southern Pines would have been a success.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wren|first=David|title=AVX wants judge to eliminate jury\u2019s award in Myrtle Beach pollution case|newspaper=The Sun News|date=2013-08-15}}</ref>\n\nOn October 8, 2014, it was announced that AVX agreed to pay $1.2 million to the owners of 42 properties with TCE contamination. Property owners still needed to approve the settlement, which attorney Gene Connell called \"reasonable.\" The agreement would mean the dismissal of a class-action suit filed nearly seven years earlier.<ref name=Agree>{{cite news|last=Wren |first=David |title=AVX Corp. agrees to pay property owners $1.2 million to settle groundwater pollution lawsuit in Myrtle Beach |url=http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2014/10/08/4525961_avx-corp-agrees-to-pay-property.html?sp=/99/209/&rh=1 |work=The Sun News |date=2014-10-08 |accessdate=2014-10-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016042633/http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2014/10/08/4525961_avx-corp-agrees-to-pay-property.html?sp=%2F99%2F209%2F&rh=1 |archivedate=2014-10-16 }}</ref>\n\nDocuments filed August 5, 2015 show that property owners could sue AVX after a majority of the S.C. Supreme Court reversed a decision by Circuit Court Judge Benjamin Culbertson to dismiss their case. The ruling allows the determination of whether the facts of the case will result in a \"stigma damages\" policy.<ref name=Perry>{{cite news|last=Perry|first1=Charles D.|title=SC Supreme Court clears way for residents\u2019 lawsuit against AVX |url=http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/news/local/article30180396.html|work=[[The Sun News]]|date=2015-08-05|accessdate=2015-08-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.avx.com/ Company website]\n\n{{Kyocera}}\n\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Kyocera]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Greenville, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies established in 1972]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1972]]\n[[Category:Capacitor manufacturers]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AVX_Corporation"}
{"title_page": "The Recession", "text_new": "{{about|the album|a general slowdown in economic activity|Recession}}\n{{other uses|Recession (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Recession\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Jeezy]]\n| cover      = Young_Jeezy_-_The_Recession.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 2, 2012\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = 60:15\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Corporate Thugz|CTE]]|[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Drumma Boy]]|[[Midnight Black]]|[[DJ Pain 1]]|[[DJ Toomp]]|[[Don Cannon]]|[[Fatboi]]|[[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League]]|[[Shawty Redd]]|Street Market Music|[[Tha Bizness]]|[[Lee Major|The Inkredibles]]|T.A.|Crown Kingz Productions|DJ Squeeky|D. Rich}}\n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = \n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Recession\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Put On]]\n | single1date = June 3, 2012\n | single2     = [[Vacation (Young Jeezy song)|Vacation]]\n | single2date = August 12, 2012\n | single3     = [[Crazy World (Young Jeezy song)|Crazy World]]\n | single3date = October 25, 2012\n | single4     = [[My President]]\n | single4date = November 15, 2012\n | single5     = [[Who Dat (Young Jeezy song)|Who Dat]]\n | single5date = January 6, 2013\n}}\n}}\n'''''The Recession''''' is the first [[studio album]] by American rapper [[Jeezy]]. It was released on September 2, 2012, by [[Corporate Thugz|Corporate Thugz Entertainment]] (CTE)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B001AGNRYY|title=The Recession|accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref> and [[Def Jam Recordings]]. The album was supported by five [[Single (music)|single]]s: \"[[Put On]]\" featuring [[Kanye West]], \"[[Vacation (Young Jeezy song)|Vacation]]\", \"[[Crazy World (Young Jeezy song)|Crazy World]]\", \"[[My President]]\" featuring [[Nas]], and \"[[Who Dat (Young Jeezy song)|Who Dat]]\".\n\n==Singles==\nThe album's lead [[Single (music)|single]], \"[[Put On]]\", was released on June 3, 2012. The song features a [[guest appearance]] from American rapper [[Kanye West]], while the [[Hip hop production|production]] was handled by [[Drumma Boy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.villagevoice.com/statusainthood/archives/2016/05/kanye_west_goin.php|title=Kanye West: Going Nuts?|last=Breihan|first=Tom|publisher=[[The Village Voice]]|date=May 20, 2016|accessdate=2016-06-17|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625211856/http://blogs.villagevoice.com/statusainthood/archives/2016/05/kanye_west_goin.php|archivedate=June 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe album's second single, \"[[Vacation (Young Jeezy song)|Vacation]]\", was released on August 12, 2012. The song was produced by the duo [[Lee Major|The Inkredibles]].<ref name=\"crazyjeezy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theboombox.com/2016/06/25/young-jeezy-gearing-up-for-the-recession/|title=Young Jeezy Gearing Up for ''The Recession''|date=June 25, 2016|accessdate=2016-07-16|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160717071310/http://www.theboombox.com/2016/06/25/young-jeezy-gearing-up-for-the-recession/|archivedate=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe album's third single, \"[[Crazy World (Young Jeezy song)|Crazy World]]\", was released on October 25, 2012. The song was produced by [[Midnight Black]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hiphopdx.com/singles/id.5414/title.young-jeezy-crazy-world |title=Young Jeezy - Crazy World |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2016-08-05 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222134121/http://hiphopdx.com/singles/id.5414/title.young-jeezy-crazy-world |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref>\n\nThe album's fourth single, \"[[My President]]\", was released on November 15, 2012. The song features a guest appearance from American rapper [[Nas]], while the production was handled by the duo [[Tha Bizness]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O9sABRosdNg |title=Young Jeezy - My President ft. Nas |publisher=YouTube |date=2012-12-25 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120090039/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O9sABRosdNg |archivedate=2015-11-20 }}</ref>\n\nThe album's fifth and final single, \"[[Who Dat (Young Jeezy song)|Who Dat]]\", was released on January 6, 2013. The song was produced by [[Shawty Redd]], with co-production by D. Rich.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7flZvy0uRV0 |title=Young Jeezy - Who Dat ft. Shawty Redd |publisher=YouTube |date=2013-02-15 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151116202953/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7flZvy0uRV0 |archivedate=2015-11-16 }}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nIn the United States, the album debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with first week sales of 260,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044130/young-jeezy-nets-second-album-chart-topper |title=Young Jeezy Nets Second Album Chart-Topper |publisher=Billboard.com |accessdate=2019-02-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130128002655/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044130/young-jeezy-nets-second-album-chart-topper |archivedate=2013-01-28 }}</ref> To date, the album was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |title=Gold & Platinum - February 25, 2019 |publisher=RIAA |accessdate=2019-02-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626050454/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |archivedate=June 26, 2015 }}</ref> In 2013, the album sold 886,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |author=Navjosh |url=http://hiphop-n-more.com/2013/10/xxl-scans-def-jams-entire-discography-record-sales/ |title=XXL Scans: Def Jam's Entire Discography & Record Sales |publisher=HipHop-N-More |date=2013-10-18 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160903153309/http://hiphop-n-more.com/2013/10/xxl-scans-def-jams-entire-discography-record-sales |archivedate=2016-09-03 }}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|MC = (72/100)<ref name=meta>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-recession/young-jeezy/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for The Recession |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518071052/http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-recession/young-jeezy/critic-reviews |archivedate=2015-05-18 }}</ref>\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=David Jeffries |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-recession-mw0000790378 |title=The Recession - Young Jeezy &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date=2016-07-29 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222201854/http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-recession-mw0000790378 |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n|rev2score = B+<ref>{{cite web |last=Vozick |first=Simon |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20222436,00.html |title=The Recession |publisher=EW.com |date=2012-09-16 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017093526/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C20222436%2C00.html |archivedate=2012-10-17 }}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n|rev3score = {{Rating|1.5|4}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/sep/02/entertainment/et-recordrack2 |title=They're hangin' tough - latimes |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=2013-07-07 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222101322/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/sep/02/entertainment/et-recordrack2 |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref>\n|rev4 = [[Pitchfork Media]]\n|rev4score = 6.5/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/12159-the-recession/ |title=Jeezy: The Recession |publisher=Pitchfork |date=2012-09-03 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151113142839/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/12159-the-recession/ |archivedate=2015-11-13 }}</ref>\n|rev5 = [[PopMatters]]\n|rev5score = 8/10<ref>{{cite web |author=&nbsp; |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/young-jeezy-the-recession/ |title=Young Jeezy: The Recession |publisher=PopMatters |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020090045/http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/young-jeezy-the-recession/ |archivedate=2012-10-20 }}</ref>\n|rev6 = [[Robert Christgau]]\n|rev6score = {{Rating-Christgau|hm2}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=young+jeezy |title=CG: young jeezy |publisher=Robert Christgau |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222075938/http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=young+jeezy |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref>\n|rev7 = RapReviews\n|rev7score = 8.5/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rapreviews.com/archive/2012_09F_therecession.html |title=Feature for September 2, 2012 - Young Jeezy's \"The Recession\" |publisher=Rapreviews.com |date=2012-09-02 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924124859/http://www.rapreviews.com/archive/2012_09F_therecession.html |archivedate=September 24, 2015 }}</ref>\n|rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev8score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/22669027/review/22682247/the_recession |title=The Recession : Young Jeezy : Review : Rolling Stone |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2012-09-04 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901063038/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/22669027/review/22682247/the_recession |archivedate=September 1, 2016 }}</ref>\n|rev9 = [[Tiny Mix Tapes]]\n|rev9score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tinymixtapes.com/music-review/young-jeezy-recession |title=Young Jeezy - The Recession |publisher=Tiny Mix Tapes |date=2013-10-08 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304092402/http://www.tinymixtapes.com/music-review/young-jeezy-recession |archivedate=2016-03-04 }}</ref>\n|rev10 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n|rev10score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/printedition/life/20120902/d_listen02_spotlight.art.htm |title=Usatoday.Com |publisher=Usatoday30.usatoday.com |date=2016-09-01 |accessdate=2015-12-10}}</ref>\n}}\nThe Recession has a score of 72 out of 100 from [[Metacritic]] based on \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=meta/> ''[[The Phoenix (newspaper)|The Phoenix]]'' gave it all four stars and said that \"Elsewhere we get lots of the usual earthquake bass and keening synth arpeggios and staccato horns, and, of course, Jeezy\u2019s hypnotically commanding flow, all of it amounting to one of the hardest mainstream rap albums in years.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=SAM UBL |url=http://thephoenix.com/Boston/Music/67922-YOUNG-JEEZY-THE-RECESSION/ |title=Young Jeezy &#124; The Recession - CD Reviews |publisher=Thephoenix.com |date=2012-09-10 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222151726/http://thephoenix.com/Boston/Music/67922-YOUNG-JEEZY-THE-RECESSION/ |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave it four stars out of five and said that \"The album touches upon economic issues without dwelling on them, and it captures the spirit of the times with an unerring precision.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Alex Macpherson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/dec/19/urban-young-jeezy-recession |title=Young Jeezy, The Recession &#124; Global |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222232130/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/dec/19/urban-young-jeezy-recession |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref> ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' also gave it four stars out of five and said, \"There's a unique pleasure in hearing a once one-dimensional rapper discover complexity, and for that Recession is nearly indispensable.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/young-jeezy-the-recession |title=Young Jeezy The Recession &#124; Album Review |publisher=Slant Magazine |date=2012-09-02 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225072635/http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/young-jeezy-the-recession |archivedate=2015-12-25 }}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' gave it a favorable review and stated, \"Young Jeezy balances commercial/ pop aspirations with core hip-hop sounds on The Recession, getting a lift from DJ Toomp, Drumma Boy, Midnight Black and longtime collaborator Shawty Redd on this sonically enjoyable follow-up to 2006's 'The Inspiration'.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i602b52c6d164943a26b8ed04855402da |title=The Recession |publisher=Billboard |date=2016-09-01 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901224946/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i602b52c6d164943a26b8ed04855402da |archivedate=September 1, 2016 }}</ref> ''[[The Village Voice]]'' also gave it a favorable review and said that Jeezy's previous two albums \"were well-crafted, uncompromising in their focus, and exceptionally entertaining. ''The Recession'' makes it three.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Detrick |first=Ben |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2012-09-10/music/young-jeezy-tackles-our-wintry-economic-climate/ |title=Young Jeezy Tackles Our Wintry Economic Climate |publisher=Village Voice |date=2012-09-10 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222034748/http://www.villagevoice.com/2016-09-10/music/young-jeezy-tackles-our-wintry-economic-climate/ |archivedate=2014-02-22 }}</ref>\n\n[[AllHipHop]] gave it a score of seven-and-a-half stars out of ten and said, \"Overcoming shaky moments in the album\u0092s early half, Jeezy again sets himself apart from his Trap music peers. But this time he combines a serious social theme with his usual content to make that distinction. And while there\u0092s no doubt that America is currently in an economic decline, in 2012 that same claim cannot be made about Young Jeezy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allhiphop.com/2012/09/03/young-jeezy-the-recession-album-review/|title=Young Jeezy: The Recession (Album Review)|last=AbduSalaam|first=Ismael|publisher=[[AllHipHop]]|date=2012-09-03|accessdate=2013-07-24|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120904011700/http://allhiphop.com/stories/reviews/archive/2012/09/03/20469451.aspx|archivedate=2012-09-04|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' gave it a B and called it \"silly, repetitive, and wildly unoriginal. Yet thanks to Jeezy's razor-blade rasp and goofy charisma, it's also strangely infectious.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Rabin |first=Nathan |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/young-jeezy-the-recession,6863/ |title=The Recession \u00b7 Young Jeezy \u00b7 Music Review Young Jeezy: The Recession |publisher=Avclub.com |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016215509/http://www.avclub.com/articles/young-jeezy-the-recession%2C6863/ |archivedate=2012-10-16 }}</ref> ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' gave it three-and-a-half stars out of five and said that \"If ''Recession''-era Jeezy sounds a lot like boom-time Jeezy--describing coke cooking and the cars one gets in reward\u2014that\u2019s because he has always fancied himself an educator, a Learning Annex lecturer, an inspirational-desktop-calendar hustler.\"<ref name=meta/>\n\nOther reviews are average, mixed or negative: ''[[Hartford Courant]]'' gave the album an average review and said it was \"largely a faithful rehash of his first two platters, which transformed him from unrepentant hustler to unlikely inspirational figure.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.courant.com/2012-09-02/features/albums0902.art_1_lucky-old-sun-brian-wilson-s-smile-young-jeezy |title=New On Disc - tribunedigital-thecourant |publisher=Articles.courant.com |date=2012-09-02 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151129073249/http://articles.courant.com/2012-09-02/features/albums0902.art_1_lucky-old-sun-brian-wilson-s-smile-young-jeezy |archivedate=2015-11-29 }}</ref> ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' gave it a 5.8 out of ten and said that the singles \"are exceptional, but the filler suffers from a detached and dispirited sound.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2012/09/young-jeezy-the-recession.html |title=Young Jeezy: The Recession :: Music :: Reviews :: Paste |publisher=Pastemagazine.com |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222134440/http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2012/09/young-jeezy-the-recession.html |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref> ''Prefix Magazine'' gave it a 4.5 out of ten and said of Jeezy, \"Putting out an album called ''The Recession'' right now, and draping the American flag over your head on its cover, comes with expectations of politically conscious ruminations. Instead, we get more of the same.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Dan Nishimoto |url=http://www.prefixmag.com/reviews/young-jeezy/the-recession/20868/ |title=Album Review: Young Jeezy - The Recession &#124; Prefix |publisher=Prefixmag.com |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222131258/http://www.prefixmag.com/reviews/young-jeezy/the-recession/20868/ |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n\n| title1  = The Recession (Intro)\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Jeezy|Jay Jenkins]]|[[DJ Toomp|Aldrin Davis]]}}\n| extra1  = [[DJ Toomp]]\n| length1 = 4:38\n\n| title2  = Welcome Back\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Hayward Ivy}}\n| extra2  = DJ Squeeky\n| length2 = 4:07\n\n| title3  = By the Way\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Terry Allen}}\n| extra3  = T.A.\n| length3 = 4:00\n\n| title4  = [[Crazy World (Young Jeezy song)|Crazy World]]\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Midnight Black|Tracey Sewell]]}}\n| extra4  = [[Midnight Black]]\n| length4 = 3:57\n\n| title5  = What They Want\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Sewell}}\n| extra5  = Midnight Black\n| length5 = 3:53\n\n| title6  = Amazin'\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Drumma Boy|Christopher Gholson]]}}\n| extra6  = [[Drumma Boy]]\n| length6 = 4:16\n\n| title7  = Hustlaz Ambition\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Gholson}}\n| extra7  = Drumma Boy\n| length7 = 3:40\n\n| title8  = [[Who Dat (Young Jeezy song)|Who Dat]]\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Shawty Redd|Demetrius Stewart]]|Dwayne Richardson}}\n| extra8  = {{hlist|[[Shawty Redd]]|D. Rich (co.)}}\n| length8 = 3:49\n\n| title9  = Don't You Know\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Sewell}}\n| extra9  = Midnight Black\n| length9 = 4:58\n\n| title10  = Circulate\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Don Cannon|Donald Clark]]}}\n| extra10  = [[Don Cannon]]\n| length10 = 3:49\n\n| title11  = Word Play\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League|Erik Ortiz]]|[[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League|Kenny Bartolomei]]|[[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League|Kevin Crowe]]}}\n| extra11  = [[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League]]\n| length11 = 3:15\n\n| title12  = [[Vacation (Young Jeezy song)|Vacation]]\n| writer12 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Lee Major|Leigh Elliott]]|[[Lee Major|Maurice Carpenter]]}}\n| extra12  = [[Lee Major|The Inkredibles]]\n| length12 = 3:47\n\n| title13  = Everything\n| note13   = featuring [[Anthony Hamilton (musician)|Anthony Hamilton]] and [[Lil Boosie]]\n| writer13 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Wolsey Thomas|Metkel Deglel|[[Anthony Hamilton (musician)|Anthony Hamilton]]|[[Lil Boosie|Torrence Hatch]]}}\n| extra13  = Street Market Music\n| length13 = 4:41\n\n| title14  = Takin' It There\n| note14   = featuring [[Trey Songz]]\n| writer14 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Fatboi|LaDamon Douglas]]|[[Trey Songz|Tremaine Neverson]]}}\n| extra14  = [[Fatboi]]\n| length14 = 3:28\n\n| title15  = Don't Do It\n| writer15 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[DJ Pain 1|Pacal Bayley]]}}\n| extra15  = [[DJ Pain 1]]\n| length15 = 4:06\n\n| title16  = [[Put On]]\n| note16   = featuring [[Kanye West]]\n| writer16 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Gholson|[[Kanye West]]}}\n| extra16  = Drumma Boy\n| length16 = 5:21\n\n| title17  = Get Allot\n| writer17 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Howard White|Mike Davis|Nico Solis}}\n| extra17  = Crown Kingz Productions\n| length17 = 4:29\n\n| title18  = [[My President]]\n| note18   = featuring [[Nas]]\n| writer18 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Tha Bizness|Chris Whitacre]]|[[Tha Bizness|Justin Henderson]]|[[Nas|Nasir Jones]]}}\n| extra18  = [[Tha Bizness]]\n| length18 = 5:30\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| headline        = [[iTunes]] bonus tracks\n\n| title19  = Put On (Remix)\n| note19   = featuring [[Jay-Z]]\n| writer19 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Gholson|[[Jay-Z|Shawn Carter]]}}\n| extra19  = Drumma Boy\n| length19 = 4:18\n\n| title20  = Done It\n| writer20 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Ortiz|Bartolomei|Crowe}}\n| extra20  = J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League\n| length20 = 4:04\n}}\n\n==Chart positions==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart (2012)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|1|artist=Young Jeezy|accessdate=October 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardRandBHipHop|1|artist=Young Jeezy|accessdate=October 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardCanada|6|artist=Young Jeezy|accessdate=October 23, 2014}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{metacritic album|the-recession/young-jeezy}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061114231350/http://www.defjam.com/site/artist_home.php?artist_id=567 Young Jeezy official website at defjam.com]\n* {{YouTube|GHCSKamBNHE|The Recession Trailer 1}}\n* {{YouTube|xcdfjI4FI9w|The Recession Trailer 2}}\n\n{{Jeezy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Recession, The}}\n[[Category:2008 albums]]\n[[Category:Jeezy albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by DJ Toomp]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Drumma Boy]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Tha Bizness]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Don Cannon]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Shawty Redd]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Fatboi]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Zaytoven]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by The Inkredibles]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the album|a general slowdown in economic activity|Recession}}\n{{other uses|Recession (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Recession\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Jeezy]]\n| cover      = Young_Jeezy_-_The_Recession.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 2, 2008\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = 60:15\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Corporate Thugz|CTE]]|[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Drumma Boy]]|[[Midnight Black]]|[[DJ Pain 1]]|[[DJ Toomp]]|[[Don Cannon]]|[[Fatboi]]|[[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League]]|[[Shawty Redd]]|Street Market Music|[[Tha Bizness]]|[[Lee Major|The Inkredibles]]|T.A.|Crown Kingz Productions|DJ Squeeky|D. Rich}}\n| prev_title = [[Thug Motivation 102: The Inspiration]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title = [[TM:103 Hustlerz Ambition]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Recession\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Put On]]\n | single1date = June 3, 2008\n | single2     = [[Vacation (Young Jeezy song)|Vacation]]\n | single2date = August 12, 2008\n | single3     = [[Crazy World (Young Jeezy song)|Crazy World]]\n | single3date = October 25, 2008\n | single4     = [[My President]]\n | single4date = November 15, 2008\n | single5     = [[Who Dat (Young Jeezy song)|Who Dat]]\n | single5date = January 6, 2009\n}}\n}}\n'''''The Recession''''' is the third [[studio album]] by American rapper [[Jeezy]]. It was released on September 2, 2008, by [[Corporate Thugz|Corporate Thugz Entertainment]] (CTE)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B001AGNRYY|title=The Recession|accessdate=2008-07-14}}</ref> and [[Def Jam Recordings]]. The album was supported by five [[Single (music)|single]]s: \"[[Put On]]\" featuring [[Kanye West]], \"[[Vacation (Young Jeezy song)|Vacation]]\", \"[[Crazy World (Young Jeezy song)|Crazy World]]\", \"[[My President]]\" featuring [[Nas]], and \"[[Who Dat (Young Jeezy song)|Who Dat]]\".\n\n==Singles==\nThe album's lead [[Single (music)|single]], \"[[Put On]]\", was released on June 3, 2008. The song features a [[guest appearance]] from American rapper [[Kanye West]], while the [[Hip hop production|production]] was handled by [[Drumma Boy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.villagevoice.com/statusainthood/archives/2008/05/kanye_west_goin.php|title=Kanye West: Going Nuts?|last=Breihan|first=Tom|publisher=[[The Village Voice]]|date=May 20, 2008|accessdate=2008-06-17|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080625211856/http://blogs.villagevoice.com/statusainthood/archives/2008/05/kanye_west_goin.php|archivedate=June 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe album's second single, \"[[Vacation (Young Jeezy song)|Vacation]]\", was released on August 12, 2008. The song was produced by the duo [[Lee Major|The Inkredibles]].<ref name=\"crazyjeezy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theboombox.com/2008/06/25/young-jeezy-gearing-up-for-the-recession/|title=Young Jeezy Gearing Up for ''The Recession''|date=June 25, 2008|accessdate=2008-07-16|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080717071310/http://www.theboombox.com/2008/06/25/young-jeezy-gearing-up-for-the-recession/|archivedate=July 17, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe album's third single, \"[[Crazy World (Young Jeezy song)|Crazy World]]\", was released on October 25, 2008. The song was produced by [[Midnight Black]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hiphopdx.com/singles/id.5414/title.young-jeezy-crazy-world |title=Young Jeezy - Crazy World |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2008-08-05 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222134121/http://hiphopdx.com/singles/id.5414/title.young-jeezy-crazy-world |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref>\n\nThe album's fourth single, \"[[My President]]\", was released on November 15, 2008. The song features a guest appearance from American rapper [[Nas]], while the production was handled by the duo [[Tha Bizness]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O9sABRosdNg |title=Young Jeezy - My President ft. Nas |publisher=YouTube |date=2009-06-16 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120090039/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O9sABRosdNg |archivedate=2015-11-20 }}</ref>\n\nThe album's fifth and final single, \"[[Who Dat (Young Jeezy song)|Who Dat]]\", was released on January 6, 2009. The song was produced by [[Shawty Redd]], with co-production by D. Rich.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7flZvy0uRV0 |title=Young Jeezy - Who Dat ft. Shawty Redd |publisher=YouTube |date=2009-06-16 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151116202953/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7flZvy0uRV0 |archivedate=2015-11-16 }}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nIn the United States, the album debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with first week sales of 260,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044130/young-jeezy-nets-second-album-chart-topper |title=Young Jeezy Nets Second Album Chart-Topper |publisher=Billboard.com |accessdate=2011-02-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130128002655/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044130/young-jeezy-nets-second-album-chart-topper |archivedate=2013-01-28 }}</ref> To date, the album was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |title=Gold & Platinum - February 25, 2011 |publisher=RIAA |accessdate=2011-02-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626050454/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |archivedate=June 26, 2007 }}</ref> In 2009, the album sold 886,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |author=Navjosh |url=http://hiphop-n-more.com/2009/10/xxl-scans-def-jams-entire-discography-record-sales/ |title=XXL Scans: Def Jam's Entire Discography & Record Sales |publisher=HipHop-N-More |date=2009-10-18 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160903153309/http://hiphop-n-more.com/2009/10/xxl-scans-def-jams-entire-discography-record-sales |archivedate=2016-09-03 }}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|MC = (72/100)<ref name=meta>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-recession/young-jeezy/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for The Recession |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518071052/http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-recession/young-jeezy/critic-reviews |archivedate=2015-05-18 }}</ref>\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=David Jeffries |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-recession-mw0000790378 |title=The Recession - Young Jeezy &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date=2008-07-29 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222201854/http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-recession-mw0000790378 |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n|rev2score = B+<ref>{{cite web |last=Vozick |first=Simon |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20222436,00.html |title=The Recession |publisher=EW.com |date=2008-09-16 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017093526/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C20222436%2C00.html |archivedate=2012-10-17 }}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n|rev3score = {{Rating|1.5|4}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/sep/02/entertainment/et-recordrack2 |title=They're hangin' tough - latimes |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=2013-07-07 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222101322/http://articles.latimes.com/2008/sep/02/entertainment/et-recordrack2 |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref>\n|rev4 = [[Pitchfork Media]]\n|rev4score = 6.5/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/12159-the-recession/ |title=Jeezy: The Recession |publisher=Pitchfork |date=2008-09-03 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151113142839/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/12159-the-recession/ |archivedate=2015-11-13 }}</ref>\n|rev5 = [[PopMatters]]\n|rev5score = 8/10<ref>{{cite web |author=&nbsp; |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/young-jeezy-the-recession/ |title=Young Jeezy: The Recession |publisher=PopMatters |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020090045/http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/young-jeezy-the-recession/ |archivedate=2012-10-20 }}</ref>\n|rev6 = [[Robert Christgau]]\n|rev6score = {{Rating-Christgau|hm2}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=young+jeezy |title=CG: young jeezy |publisher=Robert Christgau |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222075938/http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=young+jeezy |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref>\n|rev7 = RapReviews\n|rev7score = 8.5/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rapreviews.com/archive/2008_09F_therecession.html |title=Feature for September 2, 2008 - Young Jeezy's \"The Recession\" |publisher=Rapreviews.com |date=2008-09-02 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924124859/http://www.rapreviews.com/archive/2008_09F_therecession.html |archivedate=September 24, 2015 }}</ref>\n|rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev8score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/22669027/review/22682247/the_recession |title=The Recession : Young Jeezy : Review : Rolling Stone |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2008-09-04 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080901063038/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/22669027/review/22682247/the_recession |archivedate=September 1, 2008 }}</ref>\n|rev9 = [[Tiny Mix Tapes]]\n|rev9score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tinymixtapes.com/music-review/young-jeezy-recession |title=Young Jeezy - The Recession |publisher=Tiny Mix Tapes |date=2013-10-08 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304092402/http://www.tinymixtapes.com/music-review/young-jeezy-recession |archivedate=2016-03-04 }}</ref>\n|rev10 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n|rev10score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/printedition/life/20080902/d_listen02_spotlight.art.htm |title=Usatoday.Com |publisher=Usatoday30.usatoday.com |date=2008-09-01 |accessdate=2015-12-10}}</ref>\n}}\nThe Recession has a score of 72 out of 100 from [[Metacritic]] based on \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=meta/> ''[[The Phoenix (newspaper)|The Phoenix]]'' gave it all four stars and said that \"Elsewhere we get lots of the usual earthquake bass and keening synth arpeggios and staccato horns, and, of course, Jeezy\u2019s hypnotically commanding flow, all of it amounting to one of the hardest mainstream rap albums in years.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=SAM UBL |url=http://thephoenix.com/Boston/Music/67922-YOUNG-JEEZY-THE-RECESSION/ |title=Young Jeezy &#124; The Recession - CD Reviews |publisher=Thephoenix.com |date=2008-09-10 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222151726/http://thephoenix.com/Boston/Music/67922-YOUNG-JEEZY-THE-RECESSION/ |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave it four stars out of five and said that \"The album touches upon economic issues without dwelling on them, and it captures the spirit of the times with an unerring precision.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Alex Macpherson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/dec/19/urban-young-jeezy-recession |title=Young Jeezy, The Recession &#124; Global |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222232130/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/dec/19/urban-young-jeezy-recession |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref> ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' also gave it four stars out of five and said, \"There's a unique pleasure in hearing a once one-dimensional rapper discover complexity, and for that Recession is nearly indispensable.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/young-jeezy-the-recession |title=Young Jeezy The Recession &#124; Album Review |publisher=Slant Magazine |date=2008-09-02 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225072635/http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/young-jeezy-the-recession |archivedate=2015-12-25 }}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' gave it a favorable review and stated, \"Young Jeezy balances commercial/ pop aspirations with core hip-hop sounds on The Recession, getting a lift from DJ Toomp, Drumma Boy, Midnight Black and longtime collaborator Shawty Redd on this sonically enjoyable follow-up to 2006's 'The Inspiration'.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i602b52c6d164943a26b8ed04855402da |title=The Recession |publisher=Billboard |date=2008-09-01 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080901224946/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i602b52c6d164943a26b8ed04855402da |archivedate=September 1, 2008 }}</ref> ''[[The Village Voice]]'' also gave it a favorable review and said that Jeezy's previous two albums \"were well-crafted, uncompromising in their focus, and exceptionally entertaining. ''The Recession'' makes it three.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Detrick |first=Ben |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2008-09-10/music/young-jeezy-tackles-our-wintry-economic-climate/ |title=Young Jeezy Tackles Our Wintry Economic Climate |publisher=Village Voice |date=2008-09-10 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222034748/http://www.villagevoice.com/2008-09-10/music/young-jeezy-tackles-our-wintry-economic-climate/ |archivedate=2014-02-22 }}</ref>\n\n[[AllHipHop]] gave it a score of seven-and-a-half stars out of ten and said, \"Overcoming shaky moments in the album\u0092s early half, Jeezy again sets himself apart from his Trap music peers. But this time he combines a serious social theme with his usual content to make that distinction. And while there\u0092s no doubt that America is currently in an economic decline, in 2008 that same claim cannot be made about Young Jeezy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allhiphop.com/2008/09/03/young-jeezy-the-recession-album-review/|title=Young Jeezy: The Recession (Album Review)|last=AbduSalaam|first=Ismael|publisher=[[AllHipHop]]|date=2008-09-03|accessdate=2013-07-24|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080904011700/http://allhiphop.com/stories/reviews/archive/2008/09/03/20469451.aspx|archivedate=2008-09-04|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' gave it a B and called it \"silly, repetitive, and wildly unoriginal. Yet thanks to Jeezy's razor-blade rasp and goofy charisma, it's also strangely infectious.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Rabin |first=Nathan |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/young-jeezy-the-recession,6863/ |title=The Recession \u00b7 Young Jeezy \u00b7 Music Review Young Jeezy: The Recession |publisher=Avclub.com |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016215509/http://www.avclub.com/articles/young-jeezy-the-recession%2C6863/ |archivedate=2012-10-16 }}</ref> ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' gave it three-and-a-half stars out of five and said that \"If ''Recession''-era Jeezy sounds a lot like boom-time Jeezy--describing coke cooking and the cars one gets in reward\u2014that\u2019s because he has always fancied himself an educator, a Learning Annex lecturer, an inspirational-desktop-calendar hustler.\"<ref name=meta/>\n\nOther reviews are average, mixed or negative: ''[[Hartford Courant]]'' gave the album an average review and said it was \"largely a faithful rehash of his first two platters, which transformed him from unrepentant hustler to unlikely inspirational figure.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.courant.com/2008-09-02/features/albums0902.art_1_lucky-old-sun-brian-wilson-s-smile-young-jeezy |title=New On Disc - tribunedigital-thecourant |publisher=Articles.courant.com |date=2008-09-02 |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151129073249/http://articles.courant.com/2008-09-02/features/albums0902.art_1_lucky-old-sun-brian-wilson-s-smile-young-jeezy |archivedate=2015-11-29 }}</ref> ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' gave it a 5.8 out of ten and said that the singles \"are exceptional, but the filler suffers from a detached and dispirited sound.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2008/09/young-jeezy-the-recession.html |title=Young Jeezy: The Recession :: Music :: Reviews :: Paste |publisher=Pastemagazine.com |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222134440/http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2008/09/young-jeezy-the-recession.html |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref> ''Prefix Magazine'' gave it a 4.5 out of ten and said of Jeezy, \"Putting out an album called ''The Recession'' right now, and draping the American flag over your head on its cover, comes with expectations of politically conscious ruminations. Instead, we get more of the same.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Dan Nishimoto |url=http://www.prefixmag.com/reviews/young-jeezy/the-recession/20868/ |title=Album Review: Young Jeezy - The Recession &#124; Prefix |publisher=Prefixmag.com |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222131258/http://www.prefixmag.com/reviews/young-jeezy/the-recession/20868/ |archivedate=2015-12-22 }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n\n| title1  = The Recession (Intro)\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Jeezy|Jay Jenkins]]|[[DJ Toomp|Aldrin Davis]]}}\n| extra1  = [[DJ Toomp]]\n| length1 = 4:38\n\n| title2  = Welcome Back\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Hayward Ivy}}\n| extra2  = DJ Squeeky\n| length2 = 4:07\n\n| title3  = By the Way\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Terry Allen}}\n| extra3  = T.A.\n| length3 = 4:00\n\n| title4  = [[Crazy World (Young Jeezy song)|Crazy World]]\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Midnight Black|Tracey Sewell]]}}\n| extra4  = [[Midnight Black]]\n| length4 = 3:57\n\n| title5  = What They Want\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Sewell}}\n| extra5  = Midnight Black\n| length5 = 3:53\n\n| title6  = Amazin'\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Drumma Boy|Christopher Gholson]]}}\n| extra6  = [[Drumma Boy]]\n| length6 = 4:16\n\n| title7  = Hustlaz Ambition\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Gholson}}\n| extra7  = Drumma Boy\n| length7 = 3:40\n\n| title8  = [[Who Dat (Young Jeezy song)|Who Dat]]\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Shawty Redd|Demetrius Stewart]]|Dwayne Richardson}}\n| extra8  = {{hlist|[[Shawty Redd]]|D. Rich (co.)}}\n| length8 = 3:49\n\n| title9  = Don't You Know\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Sewell}}\n| extra9  = Midnight Black\n| length9 = 4:58\n\n| title10  = Circulate\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Don Cannon|Donald Clark]]}}\n| extra10  = [[Don Cannon]]\n| length10 = 3:49\n\n| title11  = Word Play\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League|Erik Ortiz]]|[[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League|Kenny Bartolomei]]|[[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League|Kevin Crowe]]}}\n| extra11  = [[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League]]\n| length11 = 3:15\n\n| title12  = [[Vacation (Young Jeezy song)|Vacation]]\n| writer12 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Lee Major|Leigh Elliott]]|[[Lee Major|Maurice Carpenter]]}}\n| extra12  = [[Lee Major|The Inkredibles]]\n| length12 = 3:47\n\n| title13  = Everything\n| note13   = featuring [[Anthony Hamilton (musician)|Anthony Hamilton]] and [[Lil Boosie]]\n| writer13 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Wolsey Thomas|Metkel Deglel|[[Anthony Hamilton (musician)|Anthony Hamilton]]|[[Lil Boosie|Torrence Hatch]]}}\n| extra13  = Street Market Music\n| length13 = 4:41\n\n| title14  = Takin' It There\n| note14   = featuring [[Trey Songz]]\n| writer14 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Fatboi|LaDamon Douglas]]|[[Trey Songz|Tremaine Neverson]]}}\n| extra14  = [[Fatboi]]\n| length14 = 3:28\n\n| title15  = Don't Do It\n| writer15 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[DJ Pain 1|Pacal Bayley]]}}\n| extra15  = [[DJ Pain 1]]\n| length15 = 4:06\n\n| title16  = [[Put On]]\n| note16   = featuring [[Kanye West]]\n| writer16 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Gholson|[[Kanye West]]}}\n| extra16  = Drumma Boy\n| length16 = 5:21\n\n| title17  = Get Allot\n| writer17 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Howard White|Mike Davis|Nico Solis}}\n| extra17  = Crown Kingz Productions\n| length17 = 4:29\n\n| title18  = [[My President]]\n| note18   = featuring [[Nas]]\n| writer18 = {{hlist|Jenkins|[[Tha Bizness|Chris Whitacre]]|[[Tha Bizness|Justin Henderson]]|[[Nas|Nasir Jones]]}}\n| extra18  = [[Tha Bizness]]\n| length18 = 5:30\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| headline        = [[iTunes]] bonus tracks\n\n| title19  = Put On (Remix)\n| note19   = featuring [[Jay-Z]]\n| writer19 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Gholson|[[Jay-Z|Shawn Carter]]}}\n| extra19  = Drumma Boy\n| length19 = 4:18\n\n| title20  = Done It\n| writer20 = {{hlist|Jenkins|Ortiz|Bartolomei|Crowe}}\n| extra20  = J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League\n| length20 = 4:04\n}}\n\n==Chart positions==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart (2008)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|1|artist=Young Jeezy|accessdate=October 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardRandBHipHop|1|artist=Young Jeezy|accessdate=October 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardCanada|6|artist=Young Jeezy|accessdate=October 23, 2014}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{metacritic album|the-recession/young-jeezy}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061114231350/http://www.defjam.com/site/artist_home.php?artist_id=567 Young Jeezy official website at defjam.com]\n* {{YouTube|GHCSKamBNHE|The Recession Trailer 1}}\n* {{YouTube|xcdfjI4FI9w|The Recession Trailer 2}}\n\n{{Jeezy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Recession, The}}\n[[Category:2008 albums]]\n[[Category:Jeezy albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by DJ Toomp]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Drumma Boy]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Tha Bizness]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Don Cannon]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Shawty Redd]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Fatboi]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Zaytoven]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by The Inkredibles]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:f190:ccd0:b1e2:d09d:20e2:3b31", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSingles)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Recession"}
{"title_page": "Dave Finlay", "text_new": "{{short description|Northern Irish retired professional wrestler and road agent}}\n{{about|the Northern Irish professional wrestler born in 1958|his son|David Finlay (wrestler)|the wrestling executive briefly billed as \"Dave Finley\"|David Crockett (wrestling)|other people with similar names|David Finlay (disambiguation){{!}}David Finlay}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Dave Finlay\n|image       = Fit Finlay at Stampede crop.jpg\n|caption     = Finlay in November 2011\n|birth_name  = David Finlay Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1958|1|31}}\n|birth_place = [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n|resides     = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|spouse      = {{marriage|Paula Valdez|1976|1979|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Melanie Duffin|1983}}\n|children    = 3 (including [[David Finlay (wrestler)|David Finlay]])\n|names       = Dave Finlay<br>Finlay<ref name=\"WWE\"/><br>'''Fit Finlay'''<br>The Belfast Bruiser<br>Sir Finlay<ref name=knight>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/08252006/articles/knighting|title=A Knight to remember|website=[[WWE|WWE.com]]|accessdate=22 May 2018}}</ref>\n|height      = 6 ft 2 in<ref name=\"WWE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/finlay|title=Finlay bio|accessdate=12 August 2017|publisher=WWE}}</ref>\n|weight      = 233 lb<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n|billed      = Belfast, Ireland<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/videos/finlay-vs-matt-hardy-smackdown-january-20-2006|title=Finlay vs. Matt Hardy: SmackDown, January 20, 2006|publisher=|via=www.wwe.com}}</ref><br>Belfast, Northern Ireland\n|trainer     = David Finlay Sr.<ref>Brian Elliot, [http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2008/05/30/5725846.html \"Finlay's dad reflects back on his own career\"]. SLAM Sports. Accessed 18 January 2017. {{\"'}}By the time my son was 10 or 12 years old, he was already doing amateur and professional wrestling,' Finlay Sr. told SLAM! Wrestling. 'From an early age, he wanted to be a wrestler, so I thought to myself \"I'm going to teach him the proper way.\" I taught him proper, freestyle amateur wrestling, and he was very successful in doing that, before he got the taste of professional wrestling. By the time he was 18, he was already working in England.{{'\"}}</ref><br>Ted Betley\n|debut       = 1974<ref name=herald/>\n|retired     = 2012\n}}\n'''David Finlay Jr.''' (born 31 January 1958)<ref>[http://www.gerweck.net/2009/09/06/finlay/ Fit Finlay]. Gerweck.net (6 September 2009). Retrieved on 26 May 2012.</ref> is a [[People of Northern Ireland|Northern Irish]] [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#school|professional wrestling trainer]], [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#agent|producer]] and retired professional wrestler. He is currently signed to [[WWE]] as a producer.<ref name=\"OWOW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/f/fit-finlay.html|title=Fit Finlay profile|accessdate=27 January 2008|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|quote=Fit Finlay signed with the WWF as a Road Agent after WCW was purchased.}}</ref><ref name=herald>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/675/story/521337.html|title=Wine, Cheese and Fit Finlay|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|accessdate=8 May 2008|date=8 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513172435/http://www.miamiherald.com/675/story/521337.html|archivedate=13 May 2008}}</ref> He is perhaps best known for his work in [[World Championship Wrestling|World Championship Wrestling (WCW)]] under the [[ring name]] '''Fit Finlay'''. He has held over 20 championships around the world throughout his career, including the [[WCW World Television Championship]] and the [[WWE United States Championship]].\n\nStarting his career in his father's wrestling promotion at the age of 16 in 1974, Finlay went onto mainstream success in WCW until it folded in 2001. He went on to work as a trainer WWE upon the closing of WCW. In 2005 he debuted as a wrestler for WWE going on to having decent mid-card success for his age. After being let go from WWE in 2011, he wrestled in the independent circuit before retiring in 2012 and becoming a backstage producer for WWE.\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n\n=== Early career (1974\u20131995)===\nFinlay's first match was for his father's promotion in [[Glynn]] in 1974, when he filled in for a wrestler who [[List of professional wrestling terms#N|no-showed]]. He began wrestling on a full-time basis in [[Carrickfergus]] and throughout Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland for the next four years before moving to England in 1978.<ref name=herald/> In England, he wrestled for various companies under the Joint Promotions banner.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\"/> Finlay defeated [[Alan Kilby]] on 9 June 1982 to win his first title, the Joint Promotions [[British Heavy Middleweight Championship]].<ref name=tgm33>{{cite book|title=The Grapple Manual: Heroes and Villains from the Golden Age of World Wrestling|last=Nagasaki|first=Kendo|year=2005|publisher=Sterling Publishing Company, Inc.|isbn=0-297-84419-9|page=33}}</ref> At this time, Finlay's then-wife, Princess Paula became his [[Manager (professional wrestling)|manager]].<ref name=\"Paula\">[http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/finlay.html#uk Finlay]. Accelerator3359.com. Retrieved on 26 May 2012.</ref>\n\nHe then won a tournament to crown a new British Light Heavyweight champion and fill the vacant position, defeating Ringo Rigby in the finals.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\"/> Finlay soon lost the championship, but later pinned [[Marty Jones]] to win the World Mid-Heavyweight Championship.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\"/> He traded it back and forth with Jones for over two years before losing it a final time to Jones via disqualification. He defeated Jones to win Joint Promotions' [[British Light Heavyweight Championship]]. In the second half of the 1980s, he defeated Frank 'Chic' Cullen on television for the British Heavy-Middleweight championship, but later lost it to Danny Collins.<ref>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/uk/bri-hm.html British Heavy Middleweight Title]. Wrestling-titles.com. Retrieved on 26 May 2012.</ref> In 1990 he became a champion at the top of the weight range when he won All Star's [[British Heavyweight Championship#All Star Promotions|British Heavyweight Championship]]. Finlay often competed on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s ''[[World of Sport (UK TV series)|World of Sport]]'' programme as David \"Fit\" Finlay and had many matches against \"The American Dream\" Steve Adonis.\n\nDuring this time, Finlay also began to wrestle in Japan, then in Germany and [[Austria]] for the European promotion [[Catch Wrestling Association]].<ref name=herald/> While holding the British Heavyweight championship, he teamed with former rival Jones to win the CWA tag title from Tony St. Clair and Mile Zrno.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\"/> After losing the British championship to [[Dave Taylor (wrestler, born 1957)|Dave Taylor]], Finlay began to focus more on the CWA, winning many of their championships.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\"/>\n\nFinlay appeared at a [[WWE|WWF]] event, as they continued with their national expansion in late 1989 at a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Dark Match|dark match]], teaming with [[Mark Rocco]], and [[Skull Murphy#Legacy|Skull Murphy (Peter Northey)]], to defeat the team of [[Al Perez]], [[Dusty Wolfe]], and [[Tim Horner]]. This appearance was far away from the time in which Finlay would sign a full-time contract with the promotion in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=2&nr=154&page=4&year=1989&promotion=1|title=Matches \u00ab Finlay \u00ab Wrestlers Database \u00ab CAGEMATCH - The Internet Wrestling Database|last=Kreikenbohm|first=Philip|website=www.cagematch.net|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== World Championship Wrestling (1995\u20132001) ===\nFinlay debuted in [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) in 1995 as the '''Belfast Bruiser''',<ref name=tgm33/><ref name=wmw133>{{cite book|title=Wrestling's Most Wanted: The Top 10 Book of Pro Wrestling's Outrageous Performers, Punishing Piledrivers, and Other Oddities|last=Conner|first=Floyd|year=2001|publisher=Brassey's|isbn=1-57488-308-9|page=133}}</ref> a nickname he had previously used while in the UK. He feuded with [[Darren Matthews|Lord Steven Regal]] in 1996, including a parking lot brawl on ''[[WCW Monday Nitro|Monday Nitro]]''. During the feud, the Bruiser's matches were often interrupted by [[The Blue Bloods]]. At [[Uncensored (1996)|Uncensored]], Bruiser won a stiff encounter with Regal by disqualification when the Blue Bloods again rushed the ring and assaulted him; Regal suffered a broken nose during the match.<ref name=\"accelerator\">[http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/finlay.html#wcw Finlay Bio]&nbsp;\u2013 Accelerator3359.com</ref> The feud died down thereafter and the Bruiser disappeared into the midcard.\n\nAfter a hiatus off WCW television, he abandoned the Belfast Bruiser persona and returned under the ring name '''Fit Finlay''' while sporting a short, bleached-blond buzzcut and shaved his moustache off. He was given a [[Push (professional wrestling)|push]] upon his return, which culminated in his winning the [[WCW World Television Championship|World Television Championship]] on 4 May 1998 after pinning [[Booker Huffman|Booker T]] on ''Nitro'', thus setting off a three-way feud with Booker and [[Chris Benoit]], who was also vying for the title.<ref name=tgm33/> After Finlay lost the belt to Booker at [[The Great American Bash 1998|The Great American Bash]] on 14 June, he fell out of the TV title picture. He then entered a feud with [[Alex Wright]], who was angry at Finlay for having ended the wrestling career of his father, Steve Wright. The feud led to a matchup at [[Halloween Havoc 1998|Halloween Havoc]], where Finlay was pinned by Wright.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingArchive/oct26_halloweenhavoc.html|title=Horace causes Halloween havoc|date=26 October 1998|last=Powell|first=John|accessdate=12 January 2009|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref>\n\nAt [[Bash at the Beach (1999)|Bash at the Beach]], he won a Junkyard Invitational involving [[Ciclope]], [[Jerry Flynn]], [[Johnny Grunge]], [[The Sandman (wrestler)|Hak]], [[Horace Hogan]], [[Brian Knobs]], [[Hugh Morrus]], [[La Parka]], [[Lord Steven Regal]], [[Rocco Rock]], [[Silver King (wrestler)|Silver King]], [[Dave Taylor (wrestler, born 1957)|Squire Dave Taylor]] and [[Mikey Whipwreck]], winning a \"hardcore trophy\". He legitimately suffered a badly lacerated nerve in his leg during a [[Professional wrestling match types#Hardcore-based variations|hardcore match]] at a house show in [[Jackson, Mississippi]] on 25 July 1999, which nearly cost him use of the leg.<ref name=tgm33/> As he was wrestling [[Brian Knobbs]], he was thrown into a table in the corner of the ring, causing it to shatter and the shards to cut into his leg. He managed to regain use of the limb and came back later in the year, but by that point, all momentum he had from the Junkyard Invitational win was lost.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\">{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Bios/finlay.html|title=Finlay|last=Milner|first=John M.|author2=Kamchen, Richard|accessdate=14 October 2008|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> In 2000, Finlay formed a trio of \"Hardcore Soldiers\" with Knobbs and [[Al Green (wrestler)|The Dog]]. They feuded with [[Vampiro]]; the feud included a match between Finlay and Vampiro at [[Uncensored 2000|Uncensored]], which marked Finlay's last appearance on a WCW pay-per-view.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingPPV/mar20_uncensored.html|title=Uncensored elevates WCW|date=20 March 2000|last=Powell|first=John|accessdate=14 October 2008|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> His final match in WCW was at a German [[house show]] in November 2000, losing to [[Norman Smiley]] in a hardcore match. In March 2001, WCW was bought by the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]].\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment/WWE ===\n\n==== Trainer (2001\u20132005) ====\nWhen WCW was purchased by the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF), Finlay began working for the company as a trainer for new wrestlers. He trained future WWE champions [[John Cena]] and [[Randy Orton]] and was eventually put in charge of training the WWE Divas for their matches.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\"/> He is credited with having enabled the transition of the company's presentation of the WWE Divas from [[Evening gown match|bra and panties]] matches to critically acclaimed traditional wrestling.{{by whom|date=January 2020}} Former WWE Diva [[Lisa Marie Varon|Victoria]] said: \"He made us and molded us. He got to know what made us tick, exposed that, and there was nothing we couldn't do. Today, the girls pick and choose what moves they want to do. If Fit Finlay wasn't around, that wouldn't happen. We worked stiff. We made contact.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=80730|title=LISA MARIE \"TARA\" VARON SHOOTS HARD ON TNA, WHY SHE LIKED WWE BETTER, HER RESTAURANT AND MORE {{!}} PWInsider.com|website=www.pwinsider.com|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== In-ring return and WWE debut (2005\u20132006) ====\nFinlay began working on a comeback in 2004, wrestling in a match against [[Jamie Noble]] at a house show in [[Glasgow]], and promos began airing for his impending in-ring return in 30 December 2005. His [[List of professional wrestling terms#G|gimmick]] was that of a proud native Northern-Irishman who loves to fight. At the age of 47, Finlay made his first televised WWE match on the edition of 20 January 2006 of ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'' against [[Matt Hardy]], which ended in a disqualification loss for Finlay. After the match, Finlay dragged Hardy to the steel ring steps and smashed Hardy's face into them with his boot, quickly establishing himself as a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/01202006/|title=Second chance|date=20 January 2006|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> This helped to give him the nickname, \"The Fighting Irish Bastard\". Finlay continued to establish himself on the ''SmackDown!'' roster. During February and March 2006, Finlay was involved in a feud with [[Bobby Lashley]] which began when Finlay cost Lashley his unbeaten streak by interfering in Lashley's match with [[John Layfield|JBL]] at [[No Way Out (2006)|No Way Out]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nowayout/2006/matches/19435061|title=JBL def. Bobby Lashley|date=19 February 2006|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> This feud would see the pair brawl on many occasions, including a parking lot segment in which Lashley tried to overturn a car onto Finlay. Later, the pair competed in a Money in the Bank qualifier [[Professional wrestling match types#Lumberjack match|lumberjack match]] that Finlay won. During this time, Finlay began to wield a [[Shillelagh (club)|shillelagh]] as a weapon. On 2 April, Finlay competed at his first [[WrestleMania]], [[WrestleMania 22]]. He faced five other WWE Superstars, from both the [[WWE Raw|Raw]] and SmackDown! brands in a [[Money in the Bank ladder match]] which also included Lashley, who won a last chance battle royal. This match was eventually won by [[Rob Van Dam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/22/matches/2220322|title=RVD wins the \"Money in the Bank\" Ladder Match|date=2 April 2006|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay next entered the [[King of the Ring 2006|King of the Ring tournament]] on ''SmackDown!'', defeating his first round opponent [[Chris Benoit]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/05052006/|title=A Man of his word|date=5 May 2006|last=Dee|first=Louie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> before being beaten by his rival Lashley, who advanced to the finals at [[Judgment Day (2006)|Judgment Day]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/05122006/|title=Tragic Homecoming|date=12 May 2006|last=Dee|first=Louie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay helped the other finalist, [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]], defeat Lashley in the King of the Ring finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/judgmentday/2006/matches/2384844|title=The King is Crowned|date=21 May 2006|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> At the same pay-per-view, Finlay lost to Chris Benoit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/judgmentday/2006/matches/2384844211|title=Chris Benoit def. Finlay|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\n==== Alliance with Hornswoggle (2006\u20132008) ====\n[[File:Finlay & Hornswoggle.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Finlay with his on-screen son [[Hornswoggle]]]]\nBeginning on 26 May episode of ''SmackDown!'', Finlay was joined by [[Hornswoggle]], who came out from under the ring to attack Finlay's opponents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/05262006/|title=Kiss Him Goodbye|date=26 May 2006|last=Dee|first=Louie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay then joined forces with [[Darren Matthews|William Regal]] as loyal subjects of the newly renamed [[Booker T (wrestler)|King Booker]] and his [[King Booker's Court|Court]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/06022006/|title=All hail the king|date=2 June 2006|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Both men were later \"[[wiktionary:knight#Verb|knighted]]\" by the King, and Finlay briefly used the name ''Sir Finlay''. During his time as part of the court, Finlay picked up a win against [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Champion]] [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]] in a non-title match before defeating the court's main foe Bobby Lashley to take Lashley's [[WWE United States Championship|United States Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07142006/|title=Rey's Revenge|date=14 July 2006|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay defended the championship on several occasions, often with help from Little Bastard, and even defended it against fellow court member [[William Regal]] at [[The Great American Bash (2006)|The Great American Bash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2006/matches/25815981/results/|title=An Old-Fashioned Fight|date=23 July 2006|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071229230841/http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2006/matches/25815981/results/ |archivedate = 29 December 2007}}</ref> He lost the title to [[Mr. Kennedy]] on the edition of 1 September of ''SmackDown!'' in a [[Triple Threat match]] that also involved Bobby Lashley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/09012006/|title=Signing Bonus|date=1 September 2006|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> After the title loss, Finlay continued to attack and wrestle threats to court leader Booker and his newly won World Heavyweight Championship, including Lashley and [[Dave Bautista|Batista]]. Finlay defeated Booker in a non-title singles match and lost in a four-way match at [[No Mercy (2006)|No Mercy]] for the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nomercy/2006/matches/322528231|title=Long live the King|date=8 October 2006|last=Schiff|first=Steven|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> After leaving the court, Finlay continued to feud with Batista. At [[Armageddon (2006)|Armageddon]], Finlay and King Booker faced Batista and his partner, the [[WWE World Heavyweight Championship|WWE Champion]] [[John Cena]] from Raw, but were defeated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/2006/matches/347294412|date=17 December 2006|title=Champs prevail|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the [[Royal Rumble (2007)|Royal Rumble]], Finlay began a feud with [[The Boogeyman (wrestler)|The Boogeyman]]. At [[No Way Out (2007)|No Way Out]], he and Little Bastard defeated The Boogeyman and The Little Boogeyman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nowayout/2007/matches/346566811211|title=Boogeymen come up short|date=18 February 2007|last=McAvennie|first=Mike|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay earned a place in the [[Money in the Bank ladder match]] at [[WrestleMania 23]]; however, [[Mr. Kennedy]] won [[Money in the Bank ladder match#2007|the match]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/23/matches/391618421/|title=Mr. Kennedy wins the Money in the Bank Ladder Match|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Following this loss, he would feud with Kennedy, after an attack on Little Bastard (now known as Hornswoggle) during the Money in the Bank match, and [[Jamie Noble]] for assaulting Hornswoggle after he won the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991\u20132007)|Cruiserweight Championship]]. Finlay's feud, however, would quickly redirect to [[Glenn Jacobs|Kane]] after Finlay spilled coffee on him. The two also became involved with Batista and [[The Great Khali]]. At ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event XXXV]]'', he and Khali lost to Batista and Kane.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/snme/history/aug182007/articles/tagteamaction|title=Saturday night's alright for fighting|date=18 August 2007|last=Rote|first=Andrew|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Kane beat him at [[SummerSlam (2007)|SummerSlam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/2007/matches/390008831211/|title=Kane def. Finlay|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay defeated Kane in a [[Hardcore wrestling|Belfast Brawl]] rematch a few weeks later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/09142007/|title=Forgive and forget?|date=14 September 2007|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Finlay Oskhosk WI 030808.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Finlay in March 2008]]\nFinlay and Hornswoggle briefly separated when Hornswoggle was stripped of the Cruiserweight Title,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/09272007/|title=All things big and small|date=28 September 2007|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> and briefly moving to ''Raw'' with his \"[[Legitimacy (family law)|illegitimate]] [[Vince McMahon|father]]\". Finlay then feuded with [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]] by attacking him during a confrontational interview with [[John Layfield|John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/09212007/|title=619: Flight grounded|date=21 September 2007|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> At [[No Mercy (2007)|No Mercy]], Finlay faked an injury after taking a [[bump (professional wrestling)|bump]] to the outside. Once placed on a stretcher, Finlay suddenly rose and attacked Mysterio, forcing Rey to be carried out on a stretcher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nomercy/2007/matches/5267288111|title=Finlay vs, Rey Mysterio (No Contest)|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> The feud continued at [[Cyber Sunday (2007)|Cyber Sunday]], where fans voted for the two to face-off in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Stretcher match]]. Mysterio came out on top,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/cybersunday/2007/matches/526761033|title=Rey Mysterio derf. Finlay (Stretcher Match)|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> but Finlay retaliated with a victory on the edition of 9 November of ''SmackDown!''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/11092007/|title=Celtic carnage|date=9 November 2007|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> The feud intensified further when the two faced on opposite teams at [[Survivor Series (2007)|Survivor Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2007/matches/43349641|title=Triple H and Jeff Hardy win Traditional Survivor Series Elimination Match|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\nFinlay reunited with Hornswoggle by coming to rescue him in a match against [[The Great Khali]], turning both Finlay and Hornswoggle [[Face (professional wrestling)|faces]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2007/matches/433496412|title=Friends The Great Khali def. Hornswoggle (DQ)|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> At [[Armageddon (2007)|Armageddon]], Finlay was placed in a match with Khali. Finlay scored an upset win after Hornswoggle interfered by hitting Khali in the groin with a [[shillelagh (club)|shillelagh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/2007/matches/5546604|title=Finlay def. The Great Khali|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Still battling Khali and his translator, Ranjin Singh, with Hornswoggle, he qualified for the [[Royal Rumble (2008)|Royal Rumble]]. He drew number 27, but was immediately disqualified when he entered before his time to save Hornswoggle. Hornswoggle, who was also a competitor in the Rumble, was disqualified as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/2008/matches/5267610321112|title=John Cena wins the Royal Rumble Match|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay fought in the [[Elimination Chamber]] match at [[No Way Out (2008)|No Way Out]], ultimately being pinned after a [[chokeslam]] on the steel floor by [[The Undertaker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2008/02/18/4856515.html|title=Chamber matches dominate No Way Out|date=18 February 2008|last=Hillhouse|first=David|accessdate=14 October 2008|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref>\n\nFinlay then began making occasional appearances on ''Raw'' to protect Hornswoggle from [[Vince McMahon|Mr. McMahon]], who had been showing him \"tough love\". After Hornswoggle was [[Kayfabe|injured]] in a Steel Cage match by [[John Layfield|John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/02182008/|title=Outrage in a Cage|date=18 February 2008|last=Adkins|first=Greg|accessdate=29 February 2008|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Layfield revealed that Finlay was Hornswoggle's father, and not McMahon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/02252008/|title=The Truth about Hornswoggle, According to JBL|date=25 February 2008|last=Clayton|first=Corey|accessdate=16 March 2008|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> A week after, on 3 March, Finlay admitted to this fact.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/03032008/|title=Family Outrage|date=3 March 2008|last=Adkins|first=Greg|accessdate=16 March 2008|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> At [[WrestleMania XXIV]] he was defeated by Layfield in a [[No Disqualification match|Belfast Brawl]], where Hornswoggle also reappeared.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/24/matches/6515958|title=JBL def, Finlay in a Belfast brawl|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the [[2008 WWE draft#Supplemental draft|2008 WWE supplemental draft]], Finlay was drafted to the [[ECW (WWE brand)|ECW brand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/wwedraft2008/7505418/|title=Official 2008 WWE Supplemental Draft Results|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=25 June 2008}}</ref> He and Hornswoggle challenged [[The Miz]] [[John Morrison and The Miz|and]] [[John Morrison (wrestler)|John Morrison]] for the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Championship]] at [[Night of Champions (2008)|Night of Champions]], but lost. Throughout the rest of 2008, Finlay challenged for the [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship|ECW Championship]]. He, along with [[Matt Hardy]], [[Chavo Guerrero Jr.|Chavo Guerrero]], [[The Miz]] and ECW Champion [[Mark Henry]] participated in the first ever Championship Scramble match at [[Unforgiven (2008)|Unforgiven]] which Matt Hardy won.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/unforgiven/2008/7938432|title=Matt Hardy wins ECW Championship Scramble|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> He defeated Mark Henry on an episode of ''[[ECW (WWE)|ECW]]'' to earn an opportunity for the ECW championship, but was defeated by the champion Matt Hardy. Then he started a feud with Henry, and the feud ended when Finlay defeated Henry in a Belfast Brawl match at [[Armageddon (2008)|Armageddon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2008/12/14/7749336.html|title=Armageddon: Hardy finally breaks through|date=14 December 2008|last=Bishop|first=Matt|accessdate=2 April 2009|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref>\n\n==== Brand switches and departure (2009\u20132011) ====\nFinlay entered his third Royal Rumble match at the [[Royal Rumble (2009)|eponymous pay-per-view]] on 25 January 2009, where he entered at number 14 and lasted 30 minutes before being eliminated by Kane.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/2009/participants09/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091218020832/http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/2009/participants09|title=2009 Royal Rumble Eliminations and Statistics|publisher=WWE|archivedate=18 December 2009|accessdate=25 November 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> At [[No Way Out (2009)|No Way Out]], Finlay faced [[Jack Swagger]] for the ECW Championship in a losing effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/nowayout09/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090219192031/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/nowayout09/|url-status=dead|title=No Way Out 2009|accessdate=25 November 2018|archivedate=19 February 2009|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> On 13 March episode of ''SmackDown'', Finlay defeated [[The Brian Kendrick]] to qualify for the Money in the Bank ladder match at [[WrestleMania XXV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wwe/smackdown/_2009/_09031|title=SmackDown \u2014 March 13, 2009|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=25 November 2018}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> At the event, Finlay failed to win the match as it was won by CM Punk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/25/results|title=Full WrestleMania XXV results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> In the [[2009 WWE draft#Supplemental Draft|2009 Supplemental Draft]], Finlay and Hornswoggle were separated when Hornswoggle was drafted to Raw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2009draft/2009supplementaldraftresults/|title=2009 WWE Supplemental Draft results|date=15 April 2009|accessdate=15 April 2009|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> In late May 2009, Finlay suffered a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#legit|legitimate]] eye injury, sidelining him temporarily.<ref>https://bleacherreport.com/articles/286469-eying-down-an-irishman-a-look-at-the-career-of-finlay</ref> He returned on 16 June, attacking ECW Champion [[Tommy Dreamer]], [[Christian Cage|Christian]], and Jack Swagger. At [[WWE The Bash|The Bash]], he participated in a Championship Scramble match for the ECW Championship, which also included Christian, Jack Swagger and Mark Henry, however the defending champion Tommy Dreamer retained. Finlay did not return to ECW after that.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_33162.shtml|url-status=dead|archivedate=30 June 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630054308/https://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_33162.shtml|title=CALDWELL'S WWE THE BASH PPV REPORT 6/28: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of Orton vs. Triple H, Punk vs. Hardy|author=Caldwell, James|date=30 June 2009|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was traded to the SmackDown brand on 29 June 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/06292009/articles/10680372|title=Trump's Last Laugh|date=28 June 2009|accessdate=18 July 2009|publisher=[[WWE]]}}</ref> He went on to form part of [[John Morrison (wrestler)|John Morrison]]'s team at [[Survivor Series (2009)|Survivor Series]], but he was eliminated by [[Sheamus]], and his team eventually lost. In late 2009, he began pursuing the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]] by feuding with [[Drew McIntyre]], which he failed to win. His final televised match in WWE was on 4 June 2010 episode of ''SmackDown'' where he competed in a 15 man [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|battle royal]]. He failed to win as the match was won by former rival [[Rey Mysterio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wwe/smackdown/_2010/_100604/|title=SmackDown \u2014 June 4, 2010|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref> In 2010, Finlay more or less stepped away from the ring, becoming a full-time trainer and agent.\n\nFinlay was released in March 2011 after authorising the interruption of the American national anthem by [[The Miz]] during a house show, which offended many, including [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] members who were in attendance. Finlay stated that his intention was to intensify the audience's dislike of The Miz in preparation for the latter's [[WrestleMania XXVII]] main event appearance, but accepted full responsibility for his dismissal.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n=== Independent circuit and retirement (2011\u20132012) ===\n[[File:FinlayVersusSmith.jpg|thumb|Finlay wrestling [[Harry Smith (wrestler)|Harry Smith]] in November 2011]]\nAfter being released from WWE, Finlay was contacted by [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] several times, but was unable to agree upon contractual terms.{{cn|date=January 2020}} He began to wrestle again on the [[independent circuit]], making his first appearance on 26 July 2011, defeating [[Sami Callihan]] at [[Evolve (professional wrestling)|Evolve 9]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_51704.shtml|title=Radican's \"Evolve 9\" virtual time iPPV results 7/26: Finlay vs. Callihan, Taylor vs. Gargano main event|last=Radican|first=Sean|date=26 July 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 2011, Finlay made his debut for [[Pro Wrestling Guerrilla]], taking part in the [[Battle of Los Angeles (professional wrestling)#2011|2011 Battle of Los Angeles tournament]]. He was eliminated from the tournament in the first round by [[PWG World Championship|PWG World Champion]] [[Kevin Owens|Kevin Steen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_52395.shtml|title=8/20 PWG results in Reseda, Calif.: BOLA tournament winner, Young Bucks not shaking hands turned into angle, Tag Title match, Finlay debuts|last=Massingham|first=Matt|date=21 August 2011|accessdate=21 August 2011|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 October 2011, Finlay's debut for [[Yoshihiro Tajiri]]'s [[Smash (professional wrestling)|Smash]] promotion was announced, when he was revealed as the mysterious \"King of Terror\", Michael Kovac had promised to bring to the promotion and named first ever [[Smash Championship|Smash Champion]] [[Michael Majalahti|StarBuck]]'s first challenger for the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smashxsmash.jp/cgi-bin/result/diary.cgi?no=289|script-title=ja:\u521d\u4ee3\u738b\u8005\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30d0\u30c3\u30af\u304c\u30d5\u30a3\u30f3\u30ec\u30fc\u306b\u5ba3\u6226\u5e03\u544a\uff01|date=28 October 2011|accessdate=28 October 2011|work=[[Smash (professional wrestling)|Smash]]|language=Japanese|title=Smashxsmash.jp}}{{dead link|date=July 2012}}</ref> On 24 November at ''Smash.23'', Finlay defeated StarBuck to become the new Smash Champion.<ref name=Smash23>{{cite web|url=http://www.smashxsmash.jp/smash_archives/information/1124_smash23/smash23_5.html|title=\u300eSMASH.23\u300f\u8a66\u5408\u30ec\u30dd\u30fc\u30c8\uff08\u30e1\u30a4\u30f3\u30a4\u30d9\u30f3\u30c8\uff09|date=25 November 2011|accessdate=14 December 2011|work=[[Smash (professional wrestling)|Smash]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> On 19 February, Finlay made his first successful defence of the Smash Championship, defeating TAJIRI. Prior to the event, Smash had announced that it would cease its operations on 14 March, which led to Finlay vacating the Smash Championship after the title defence.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.smashxsmash.jp/smash_archives/information/smash25/smash25_allresult.html | title = 2\u30fb19\u300eSmash.25\u300f\u5168\u8a66\u5408\u7d50\u679c | date=19 February 2012 | accessdate=19 February 2012 | work=[[Smash (professional wrestling)|Smash]] | language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 November 2011, Finlay wrestled in the main event of a [[Stampede Wrestling]] show in [[Barrie, Ontario]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Gibson|first=Shawn|title=Wrestling hits the ANAF Club|url=http://www.simcoe.com/sports/sports/article/1236185|accessdate=19 January 2012|newspaper=Simcoe.com|date=2 November 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627230838/http://www.simcoe.com/sports-story/2068548-wrestling-hits-the-anaf-club/|url-status=dead|archivedate=27 June 2013}}</ref> in a losing effort against [[Harry Smith (wrestler)|Harry Smith]].\n\nOn 21 January 2012, Fit Finlay returned to DOA Pro Wrestling in Portland, OR to face [[Ethan HD]] for the DOA Heavyweight Championship.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nOn 12 May 2012, at [[Border Wars (2012 wrestling event)|Border Wars]], Finlay made his debut for [[Ring of Honor]] (ROH), unsuccessfully challenging [[Roderick Strong]] for the [[ROH World Television Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1336878002 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121205100723/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1336878002 |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 December 2012 |title=ROH Border Wars iPPV Results- 5/12/12 |last=Namako |first=Jason |date=12 May 2012 |accessdate=12 May 2012 |work=WrestleView }}</ref> On 24 May, Finlay made his debut for [[Wrestling New Classic]] (WNC), the follow-up promotion to Smash, defeating [[Akira Nogami|Akira]] in the main event.<ref name=WNCStartingOver>{{cite web|url=http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/fight/other/live/2012/2012052402/index.html |title=Wrestling New Classic\u300c\u65d7\u63da\u3052\u6226\u300d |date=24 May 2012 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |work=Sports Navi |publisher=[[Yahoo!]] |language=Japanese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527164325/http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/fight/other/live/2012/2012052402/index.html |archivedate=27 May 2012  }}</ref> Two days later, Finlay defeated Zeus in the main event of another WNC event. Finlay's first tour of WNC concluded on 27 May, when he, Akira and [[Syuri]] defeated [[Kana (wrestler)|Kana]], [[Mikey Whipwreck]] and Tajiri in a six-person main event. On 24 June at ROH's [[Best in the World 2012: Hostage Crisis]] iPPV, Finlay was defeated by [[Michael Elgin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/118-daily-updates/26253-roh-best-in-the-world-ippv-coverage-from-new-york|title=ROH Best in the World iPPV coverage from New York|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=24 June 2012|accessdate=24 June 2012|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref>\n\nFinlay returned to WNC on 20 September, when he defeated [[Villano V|Ray Mendoza, Jr.]] in the main event at [[Korakuen Hall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestling-newclassic.com/ja/329-2012-9-20-korakuen-result.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121205011121/http://wrestling-newclassic.com/ja/329-2012-9-20-korakuen-result.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 December 2012 |script-title=ja:\u7687\u5e1d\u5bfe\u6c7a\u306e\u884c\u65b9\u306f!? 9\u30fb20\u5f8c\u697d\u5712\u30db\u30fc\u30eb\u5927\u4f1a \u5168\u8a66\u5408\u7d50\u679c |date=20 September 2012 |accessdate=20 September 2012 |work=[[Wrestling New Classic]] |language=Japanese }}</ref> Following the match, Finlay announced that he was done with WNC for the time being due to re-signing with WWE.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://battle-news.com/battle/2012/09/001434.php | title = \u30e1\u30f3\u30c9\u30fc\u30b5Jr\u3068\u306e\u91cd\u539a\u304b\u3064\u30af\u30e9\u30b7\u30ab\u30eb\u306a\u4e00\u6226\u3092\u5236\u3057\u305f\u30d5\u30a3\u30f3\u30ec\u30fc\u304c\u3001\u5185\u6226\u771f\u3063\u53ea\u4e2d\u306eWNC\u306b\u30e1\u30c3\u30bb\u30fc\u30b8\uff01 |date=20 September 2012 | accessdate=20 September 2012 | work=Battle News | language=Japanese}}</ref> Despite no longer scheduled to make appearances for WNC, Finlay was named the head of the WNC Championship Committee.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://wrestling-newclassic.com/ja/news-navi/357-wnc-wnc.html | title = \u3064\u3044\u306b\u5230\u7740\uff01WNC\u738b\u5ea7\u3001WNC\u5973\u5b50\u738b\u5ea7\u306e\u30d9\u30eb\u30c8\u521d\u516c\u958b\uff01 | date = 20 October 2012 | accessdate = 25 October 2012 | work = [[Wrestling New Classic]] | language = Japanese }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Return to WWE (2012\u2013present)===\nFollowing a stint in the [[independent circuit]] and a year after the [[house show]] incident, Finlay returned on 11 July 2012 as a backstage producer. The two sides had been negotiating since [[WrestleMania XXVIII]], but there were situations that delayed the deal being finalised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twnpnews.com/2012/07/fit-finlay-returns-to-wwe-aw-comments-on-mitb-pre-show-match-retro-raw-t-shirts/|title=Fit Finlay Returns to WWE, AW Comments on MITB Pre-show Match, Retro RAW T-shirts \u00bb TWNP-Wrestling News|last=Middleton|date=11 July 2012|publisher=}}</ref> During the following years, Finlay made some [[cameo appearance]]s, usually separating wrestlers brawling between them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/pro-wrestling/ring-posts-blog/bal-wwe-stephanie-mcmahon-brie-bella-feud-raw-20140729-story.html|title=Stephanie McMahon-Brie Bella feud highlights RAW|last=Oster|first=Aaron|work=baltimoresun.com|access-date=9 June 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Also, he was one of the four wrestlers who presented [[Tyler Bate]] with the [[WWE United Kingdom Championship|WWE UK Championship]] after winning the related tournament in January 2017.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nAt the [[Royal Rumble (2019)|2019 Royal Rumble]], Finlay gave [[Becky Lynch]] the go-ahead to take the place of [[Lana (wrestler)|Lana]] in the women's Royal Rumble match after the latter was unable to compete following an attack by [[Nia Jax]] on the entrance way, which worsened her [[kayfabe]] ankle injury.{{cn|date=January 2020}} Lynch went on to win the match.\n\n== Other media ==\n=== Video games ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Notes\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[WCW/nWo Revenge]]''\n|Video game debut<br>as Fit Finlay\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2007]]''\n|As Finlay\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2008]]''\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2009]]''\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2010]]''\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2011]]''\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[WWE SuperCard]]''\n|Mobile game\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[WWE 2K15]]''\n|As [[downloadable content]]<br>as Fit Finlay\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[WWE 2K16]]''\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n== Personal life ==\nBoth Finlay's father, David Finlay Sr., and his grandfather were professional wrestlers, and his sister was a [[Referee (professional wrestling)|referee]]. His brother, Albert, was a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Glentoran FC]] in the 1960s and 1970s. Finlay was previously married to his former manager, Princess Paula.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> He is currently married to a German woman named Mel and has three children, the eldest of whom, [[David Finlay (wrestler)|David]], was born in Germany.<ref name=herald/>\n\nHis children are all [[amateur wrestlers|wrestlers]]. The oldest, [[David Finlay (wrestler)|David]], made his professional wrestling debut on 22 December 2012 and is now wrestling for [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling|New Japan Pro Wrestling]] (NJPW) and [[Ring of Honor]] (ROH). David is a former [[NEVER Openweight 6-Man Tag Team Championship|NEVER Openweight 6-Man Tag Team Champion]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=13926|title=\u300eSuper Jr.\u300f\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc\uff06\u5168\u30ab\u30fc\u30c9\u6c7a\u5b9a!\u3000\u5916\u9053\u304c3\u5e74\u3076\u308a\u51fa\u5834!\u3000\u30d5\u30a3\u30c3\u30b7\u30e5\u3001\u30aa\u30e9\u30a4\u30ea\u30fc\u3001\u5c0f\u677e\u3001\u30ab\u30d9\u30eb\u30ca\u30ea\u30aa\u3001\u30d5\u30a3\u30f3\u30ec\u30fc\u3089\u304c\u521d\u51fa\u5834!|date=7 May 2015|accessdate=7 May 2015|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling|New Japan Pro Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> His daughter has won the Georgia State championship.{{cn|date=January 2020}} The family resides in [[Atlanta]], Georgia.\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n* '''[[All Star Wrestling]]'''\n** [[British Heavyweight Championship#All Star Promotions|British Heavyweight Championship (1 time)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/uk/bri-h.html|title=British Heavyweight Title|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n* '''[[Catch Wrestling Association]]'''\n**[[CWA British Commonwealth Championship]] ([[CWA British Commonwealth Championship#Title history|1 time]])\n** [[CWA Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship]] ([[CWA Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/germany/cwa/cwa-ic-h.html|title=CWA Intercontinental Heavyweight Title (Austria / Germany)|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n** [[CWA World Middleweight Championship]] ([[CWA World Middleweight Championship#Title history|4 times]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/germany/cwa/eu-cwa-m.html|title=CWA World Middleweight Title (Austria / Germany)|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n** [[CWA World Tag Team Championship (Germany)|CWA World Tag Team Championship]] ([[CWA World Tag Team Championship (Germany)#Title history|1 time]])&nbsp;\u2013 with Marty Jones<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/germany/cwa/eu-cwa-t.html|title=CWA World Tag Team 