 SmackDown]] <small>([[Chris Jericho]], [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]], [[R-Truth]], [[Matt Hardy]], [[David Hart Smith]] and [[Tyson Kidd]])</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wwebraggingrights/2009|title=Bragging Rights 2009 results|website=[[WWE]].com|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.cultofwhatever.com/2012/04/dave-fit-finlay-interview/ Dave Finlay Interview]\n*{{wwe superstar|name = Finlay}}\n*{{twitter|ringfox1}}\n*{{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n{{Navboxes|\n|list1=\n{{CWA British Commonwealth Championship}}\n{{CWA Intercontinental Heavyweight Champions}}\n{{CWA World Middleweight Championship}}\n{{CWA World Tag Team Championship}}\n{{WWE United States Championship}}\n{{WCW World Television Championship}}\n{{WWE personnel}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finlay, Dave}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Expatriate sportspeople from Northern Ireland in the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male professional wrestlers from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:NWA/WCW World Television Champions]]\n[[Category:NWA/WCW/WWE United States Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:People from Carrickfergus]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling executives]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling managers and valets]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling trainers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Belfast]]\n[[Category:Ulster Scots people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Northern Irish retired professional wrestler and road agent}}\n{{about|the Northern Irish professional wrestler born in 1958|his son|David Finlay (wrestler)|the wrestling executive briefly billed as \"Dave Finley\"|David Crockett (wrestling)|other people with similar names|David Finlay (disambiguation){{!}}David Finlay}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Dave Finlay\n|image       = Fit Finlay at Stampede crop.jpg\n|caption     = Finlay in November 2011\n|birth_name  = David Finlay Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1958|1|31}}\n|birth_place = [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n|resides     = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|spouse      = {{marriage|Paula Valdez|1976|1979|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Melanie Duffin|1983}}\n|children    = 3 (including [[David Finlay (wrestler)|David Finlay]])\n|names       = Dave Finlay<br>Finlay<ref name=\"WWE\"/><br>'''Fit Finlay'''<br>The Belfast Bruiser<br>Sir Finlay<ref name=knight>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/08252006/articles/knighting|title=A Knight to remember|website=[[WWE|WWE.com]]|accessdate=22 May 2018}}</ref>\n|height      = 6 ft 2 in<ref name=\"WWE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/finlay|title=Finlay bio|accessdate=12 August 2017|publisher=WWE}}</ref>\n|weight      = 233 lb<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n|billed      = Belfast, Ireland<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/videos/finlay-vs-matt-hardy-smackdown-january-20-2006|title=Finlay vs. Matt Hardy: SmackDown, January 20, 2006|publisher=|via=www.wwe.com}}</ref><br>Belfast, Northern Ireland\n|trainer     = David Finlay Sr.<ref>Brian Elliot, [http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2008/05/30/5725846.html \"Finlay's dad reflects back on his own career\"]. SLAM Sports. Accessed 18 January 2017. {{\"'}}By the time my son was 10 or 12 years old, he was already doing amateur and professional wrestling,' Finlay Sr. told SLAM! Wrestling. 'From an early age, he wanted to be a wrestler, so I thought to myself \"I'm going to teach him the proper way.\" I taught him proper, freestyle amateur wrestling, and he was very successful in doing that, before he got the taste of professional wrestling. By the time he was 18, he was already working in England.{{'\"}}</ref><br>Ted Betley\n|debut       = 1974<ref name=herald/>\n|retired     = 2012\n}}\n'''David Finlay Jr.''' (born 31 January 1958)<ref>[http://www.gerweck.net/2009/09/06/finlay/ Fit Finlay]. Gerweck.net (6 September 2009). Retrieved on 26 May 2012.</ref> is a [[People of Northern Ireland|Northern Irish]] [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#school|professional wrestling trainer]], [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#agent|producer]] and retired professional wrestler. He is currently signed to [[WWE]] as a producer.<ref name=\"OWOW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/f/fit-finlay.html|title=Fit Finlay profile|accessdate=27 January 2008|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|quote=Fit Finlay signed with the WWF as a Road Agent after WCW was purchased.}}</ref><ref name=herald>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/675/story/521337.html|title=Wine, Cheese and Fit Finlay|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|accessdate=8 May 2008|date=8 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513172435/http://www.miamiherald.com/675/story/521337.html|archivedate=13 May 2008}}</ref> He is perhaps best known for his work in [[World Championship Wrestling|World Championship Wrestling (WCW)]] under the [[ring name]] '''Fit Finlay'''. He has held over 20 championships around the world throughout his career, including the [[WCW World Television Championship]] and the [[WWE United States Championship]].\n\nStarting his career in his father's wrestling promotion at the age of 16 in 1974, Finlay went onto mainstream success in WCW until it folded in 2001. He went on to work as a trainer WWE upon the closing of WCW. In 2005 he debuted as a wrestler for WWE going on to having decent mid-card success for his age. After being let go from WWE he wrestled in the independent circuit for a short time, before retiring in 2012 and becoming a backstage producer for WWE.\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n\n=== Early career (1974\u20131995)===\nFinlay's first match was for his father's promotion in [[Glynn]] in 1974, when he filled in for a wrestler who [[List of professional wrestling terms#N|no-showed]]. He began wrestling on a full-time basis in [[Carrickfergus]] and throughout Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland for the next four years before moving to England in 1978.<ref name=herald/> In England, he wrestled for various companies under the Joint Promotions banner.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\"/> Finlay defeated [[Alan Kilby]] on 9 June 1982 to win his first title, the Joint Promotions [[British Heavy Middleweight Championship]].<ref name=tgm33>{{cite book|title=The Grapple Manual: Heroes and Villains from the Golden Age of World Wrestling|last=Nagasaki|first=Kendo|year=2005|publisher=Sterling Publishing Company, Inc.|isbn=0-297-84419-9|page=33}}</ref> At this time, Finlay's then-wife, Princess Paula became his [[Manager (professional wrestling)|manager]].<ref name=\"Paula\">[http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/finlay.html#uk Finlay]. Accelerator3359.com. Retrieved on 26 May 2012.</ref>\n\nHe then won a tournament to crown a new British Light Heavyweight champion and fill the vacant position, defeating Ringo Rigby in the finals.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\"/> Finlay soon lost the championship, but later pinned [[Marty Jones]] to win the World Mid-Heavyweight Championship.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\"/> He traded it back and forth with Jones for over two years before losing it a final time to Jones via disqualification. He defeated Jones to win Joint Promotions' [[British Light Heavyweight Championship]]. In the second half of the 1980s, he defeated Frank 'Chic' Cullen on television for the British Heavy-Middleweight championship, but later lost it to Danny Collins.<ref>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/uk/bri-hm.html British Heavy Middleweight Title]. Wrestling-titles.com. Retrieved on 26 May 2012.</ref> In 1990 he became a champion at the top of the weight range when he won All Star's [[British Heavyweight Championship#All Star Promotions|British Heavyweight Championship]]. Finlay often competed on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s ''[[World of Sport (UK TV series)|World of Sport]]'' programme as David \"Fit\" Finlay and had many matches against \"The American Dream\" Steve Adonis.\n\nDuring this time, Finlay also began to wrestle in Japan, then in Germany and [[Austria]] for the European promotion [[Catch Wrestling Association]].<ref name=herald/> While holding the British Heavyweight championship, he teamed with former rival Jones to win the CWA tag title from Tony St. Clair and Mile Zrno.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\"/> After losing the British championship to [[Dave Taylor (wrestler, born 1957)|Dave Taylor]], Finlay began to focus more on the CWA, winning many of their championships.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\"/>\n\nFinlay appeared at a [[WWE|WWF]] event, as they continued with their national expansion in late 1989 at a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Dark Match|dark match]], teaming with [[Mark Rocco]], and [[Skull Murphy#Legacy|Skull Murphy (Peter Northey)]], to defeat the team of [[Al Perez]], [[Dusty Wolfe]], and [[Tim Horner]]. This appearance was far away from the time in which Finlay would sign a full-time contract with the promotion in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=2&nr=154&page=4&year=1989&promotion=1|title=Matches \u00ab Finlay \u00ab Wrestlers Database \u00ab CAGEMATCH - The Internet Wrestling Database|last=Kreikenbohm|first=Philip|website=www.cagematch.net|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== World Championship Wrestling (1995\u20132001) ===\nFinlay debuted in [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) in 1995 as the '''Belfast Bruiser''',<ref name=tgm33/><ref name=wmw133>{{cite book|title=Wrestling's Most Wanted: The Top 10 Book of Pro Wrestling's Outrageous Performers, Punishing Piledrivers, and Other Oddities|last=Conner|first=Floyd|year=2001|publisher=Brassey's|isbn=1-57488-308-9|page=133}}</ref> a nickname he had previously used while in the UK. He feuded with [[Darren Matthews|Lord Steven Regal]] in 1996, including a parking lot brawl on ''[[WCW Monday Nitro|Monday Nitro]]''. During the feud, the Bruiser's matches were often interrupted by [[The Blue Bloods]]. At [[Uncensored (1996)|Uncensored]], Bruiser won a stiff encounter with Regal by disqualification when the Blue Bloods again rushed the ring and assaulted him; Regal suffered a broken nose during the match.<ref name=\"accelerator\">[http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/finlay.html#wcw Finlay Bio]&nbsp;\u2013 Accelerator3359.com</ref> The feud died down thereafter and the Bruiser disappeared into the midcard.\n\nAfter a hiatus off WCW television, he abandoned the Belfast Bruiser persona and returned under the ring name '''Fit Finlay''' while sporting a short, bleached-blond buzzcut and shaved his moustache off. He was given a [[Push (professional wrestling)|push]] upon his return, which culminated in his winning the [[WCW World Television Championship|World Television Championship]] on 4 May 1998 after pinning [[Booker Huffman|Booker T]] on ''Nitro'', thus setting off a three-way feud with Booker and [[Chris Benoit]], who was also vying for the title.<ref name=tgm33/> After Finlay lost the belt to Booker at [[The Great American Bash 1998|The Great American Bash]] on 14 June, he fell out of the TV title picture. He then entered a feud with [[Alex Wright]], who was angry at Finlay for having ended the wrestling career of his father, Steve Wright. The feud led to a matchup at [[Halloween Havoc 1998|Halloween Havoc]], where Finlay was pinned by Wright.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingArchive/oct26_halloweenhavoc.html|title=Horace causes Halloween havoc|date=26 October 1998|last=Powell|first=John|accessdate=12 January 2009|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref>\n\nAt [[Bash at the Beach (1999)|Bash at the Beach]], he won a Junkyard Invitational involving [[Ciclope]], [[Jerry Flynn]], [[Johnny Grunge]], [[The Sandman (wrestler)|Hak]], [[Horace Hogan]], [[Brian Knobs]], [[Hugh Morrus]], [[La Parka]], [[Lord Steven Regal]], [[Rocco Rock]], [[Silver King (wrestler)|Silver King]], [[Dave Taylor (wrestler, born 1957)|Squire Dave Taylor]] and [[Mikey Whipwreck]], winning a \"hardcore trophy\". He legitimately suffered a badly lacerated nerve in his leg during a [[Professional wrestling match types#Hardcore-based variations|hardcore match]] at a house show in [[Jackson, Mississippi]] on 25 July 1999, which nearly cost him use of the leg.<ref name=tgm33/> As he was wrestling [[Brian Knobbs]], he was thrown into a table in the corner of the ring, causing it to shatter and the shards to cut into his leg. He managed to regain use of the limb and came back later in the year, but by that point, all momentum he had from the Junkyard Invitational win was lost.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\">{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Bios/finlay.html|title=Finlay|last=Milner|first=John M.|author2=Kamchen, Richard|accessdate=14 October 2008|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> In 2000, Finlay formed a trio of \"Hardcore Soldiers\" with Knobbs and [[Al Green (wrestler)|The Dog]]. They feuded with [[Vampiro]]; the feud included a match between Finlay and Vampiro at [[Uncensored 2000|Uncensored]], which marked Finlay's last appearance on a WCW pay-per-view.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingPPV/mar20_uncensored.html|title=Uncensored elevates WCW|date=20 March 2000|last=Powell|first=John|accessdate=14 October 2008|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> His final match in WCW was at a German [[house show]] in November 2000, losing to [[Norman Smiley]] in a hardcore match. In March 2001, WCW was bought by the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]].\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment/WWE ===\n\n==== Trainer (2001\u20132005) ====\nWhen WCW was purchased by the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF), Finlay began working for the company as a trainer for new wrestlers. He trained future WWE champions [[John Cena]] and [[Randy Orton]] and was eventually put in charge of training the WWE Divas for their matches.<ref name=\"SLAMbio\"/> He is credited with having enabled the transition of the company's presentation of the WWE Divas from [[Evening gown match|bra and panties]] matches to critically acclaimed traditional wrestling.{{by whom|date=January 2020}} Former WWE Diva [[Lisa Marie Varon|Victoria]] said: \"He made us and molded us. He got to know what made us tick, exposed that, and there was nothing we couldn't do. Today, the girls pick and choose what moves they want to do. If Fit Finlay wasn't around, that wouldn't happen. We worked stiff. We made contact.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=80730|title=LISA MARIE \"TARA\" VARON SHOOTS HARD ON TNA, WHY SHE LIKED WWE BETTER, HER RESTAURANT AND MORE {{!}} PWInsider.com|website=www.pwinsider.com|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== In-ring return and WWE debut (2005\u20132006) ====\nFinlay began working on a comeback in 2004, wrestling in a match against [[Jamie Noble]] at a house show in [[Glasgow]], and promos began airing for his impending in-ring return in 30 December 2005. His [[List of professional wrestling terms#G|gimmick]] was that of a proud native Northern-Irishman who loves to fight. At the age of 47, Finlay made his first televised WWE match on the edition of 20 January 2006 of ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'' against [[Matt Hardy]], which ended in a disqualification loss for Finlay. After the match, Finlay dragged Hardy to the steel ring steps and smashed Hardy's face into them with his boot, quickly establishing himself as a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/01202006/|title=Second chance|date=20 January 2006|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> This helped to give him the nickname, \"The Fighting Irish Bastard\". Finlay continued to establish himself on the ''SmackDown!'' roster. During February and March 2006, Finlay was involved in a feud with [[Bobby Lashley]] which began when Finlay cost Lashley his unbeaten streak by interfering in Lashley's match with [[John Layfield|JBL]] at [[No Way Out (2006)|No Way Out]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nowayout/2006/matches/19435061|title=JBL def. Bobby Lashley|date=19 February 2006|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> This feud would see the pair brawl on many occasions, including a parking lot segment in which Lashley tried to overturn a car onto Finlay. Later, the pair competed in a Money in the Bank qualifier [[Professional wrestling match types#Lumberjack match|lumberjack match]] that Finlay won. During this time, Finlay began to wield a [[Shillelagh (club)|shillelagh]] as a weapon. On 2 April, Finlay competed at his first [[WrestleMania]], [[WrestleMania 22]]. He faced five other WWE Superstars, from both the [[WWE Raw|Raw]] and SmackDown! brands in a [[Money in the Bank ladder match]] which also included Lashley, who won a last chance battle royal. This match was eventually won by [[Rob Van Dam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/22/matches/2220322|title=RVD wins the \"Money in the Bank\" Ladder Match|date=2 April 2006|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay next entered the [[King of the Ring 2006|King of the Ring tournament]] on ''SmackDown!'', defeating his first round opponent [[Chris Benoit]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/05052006/|title=A Man of his word|date=5 May 2006|last=Dee|first=Louie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> before being beaten by his rival Lashley, who advanced to the finals at [[Judgment Day (2006)|Judgment Day]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/05122006/|title=Tragic Homecoming|date=12 May 2006|last=Dee|first=Louie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay helped the other finalist, [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]], defeat Lashley in the King of the Ring finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/judgmentday/2006/matches/2384844|title=The King is Crowned|date=21 May 2006|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> At the same pay-per-view, Finlay lost to Chris Benoit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/judgmentday/2006/matches/2384844211|title=Chris Benoit def. Finlay|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\n==== Alliance with Hornswoggle (2006\u20132008) ====\n[[File:Finlay & Hornswoggle.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Finlay with his on-screen son [[Hornswoggle]]]]\nBeginning on 26 May episode of ''SmackDown!'', Finlay was joined by [[Hornswoggle]], who came out from under the ring to attack Finlay's opponents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/05262006/|title=Kiss Him Goodbye|date=26 May 2006|last=Dee|first=Louie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay then joined forces with [[Darren Matthews|William Regal]] as loyal subjects of the newly renamed [[Booker T (wrestler)|King Booker]] and his [[King Booker's Court|Court]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/06022006/|title=All hail the king|date=2 June 2006|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Both men were later \"[[wiktionary:knight#Verb|knighted]]\" by the King, and Finlay briefly used the name ''Sir Finlay''. During his time as part of the court, Finlay picked up a win against [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Champion]] [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]] in a non-title match before defeating the court's main foe Bobby Lashley to take Lashley's [[WWE United States Championship|United States Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07142006/|title=Rey's Revenge|date=14 July 2006|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay defended the championship on several occasions, often with help from Little Bastard, and even defended it against fellow court member [[William Regal]] at [[The Great American Bash (2006)|The Great American Bash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2006/matches/25815981/results/|title=An Old-Fashioned Fight|date=23 July 2006|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071229230841/http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2006/matches/25815981/results/ |archivedate = 29 December 2007}}</ref> He lost the title to [[Mr. Kennedy]] on the edition of 1 September of ''SmackDown!'' in a [[Triple Threat match]] that also involved Bobby Lashley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/09012006/|title=Signing Bonus|date=1 September 2006|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> After the title loss, Finlay continued to attack and wrestle threats to court leader Booker and his newly won World Heavyweight Championship, including Lashley and [[Dave Bautista|Batista]]. Finlay defeated Booker in a non-title singles match and lost in a four-way match at [[No Mercy (2006)|No Mercy]] for the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nomercy/2006/matches/322528231|title=Long live the King|date=8 October 2006|last=Schiff|first=Steven|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> After leaving the court, Finlay continued to feud with Batista. At [[Armageddon (2006)|Armageddon]], Finlay and King Booker faced Batista and his partner, the [[WWE World Heavyweight Championship|WWE Champion]] [[John Cena]] from Raw, but were defeated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/2006/matches/347294412|date=17 December 2006|title=Champs prevail|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the [[Royal Rumble (2007)|Royal Rumble]], Finlay began a feud with [[The Boogeyman (wrestler)|The Boogeyman]]. At [[No Way Out (2007)|No Way Out]], he and Little Bastard defeated The Boogeyman and The Little Boogeyman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nowayout/2007/matches/346566811211|title=Boogeymen come up short|date=18 February 2007|last=McAvennie|first=Mike|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay earned a place in the [[Money in the Bank ladder match]] at [[WrestleMania 23]]; however, [[Mr. Kennedy]] won [[Money in the Bank ladder match#2007|the match]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/23/matches/391618421/|title=Mr. Kennedy wins the Money in the Bank Ladder Match|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Following this loss, he would feud with Kennedy, after an attack on Little Bastard (now known as Hornswoggle) during the Money in the Bank match, and [[Jamie Noble]] for assaulting Hornswoggle after he won the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991\u20132007)|Cruiserweight Championship]]. Finlay's feud, however, would quickly redirect to [[Glenn Jacobs|Kane]] after Finlay spilled coffee on him. The two also became involved with Batista and [[The Great Khali]]. At ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event XXXV]]'', he and Khali lost to Batista and Kane.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/snme/history/aug182007/articles/tagteamaction|title=Saturday night's alright for fighting|date=18 August 2007|last=Rote|first=Andrew|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Kane beat him at [[SummerSlam (2007)|SummerSlam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/2007/matches/390008831211/|title=Kane def. Finlay|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay defeated Kane in a [[Hardcore wrestling|Belfast Brawl]] rematch a few weeks later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/09142007/|title=Forgive and forget?|date=14 September 2007|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Finlay Oskhosk WI 030808.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Finlay in March 2008]]\nFinlay and Hornswoggle briefly separated when Hornswoggle was stripped of the Cruiserweight Title,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/09272007/|title=All things big and small|date=28 September 2007|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> and briefly moving to ''Raw'' with his \"[[Legitimacy (family law)|illegitimate]] [[Vince McMahon|father]]\". Finlay then feuded with [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]] by attacking him during a confrontational interview with [[John Layfield|John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/09212007/|title=619: Flight grounded|date=21 September 2007|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> At [[No Mercy (2007)|No Mercy]], Finlay faked an injury after taking a [[bump (professional wrestling)|bump]] to the outside. Once placed on a stretcher, Finlay suddenly rose and attacked Mysterio, forcing Rey to be carried out on a stretcher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nomercy/2007/matches/5267288111|title=Finlay vs, Rey Mysterio (No Contest)|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> The feud continued at [[Cyber Sunday (2007)|Cyber Sunday]], where fans voted for the two to face-off in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Stretcher match]]. Mysterio came out on top,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/cybersunday/2007/matches/526761033|title=Rey Mysterio derf. Finlay (Stretcher Match)|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> but Finlay retaliated with a victory on the edition of 9 November of ''SmackDown!''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/11092007/|title=Celtic carnage|date=9 November 2007|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|accessdate=20 November 2007|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> The feud intensified further when the two faced on opposite teams at [[Survivor Series (2007)|Survivor Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2007/matches/43349641|title=Triple H and Jeff Hardy win Traditional Survivor Series Elimination Match|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\nFinlay reunited with Hornswoggle by coming to rescue him in a match against [[The Great Khali]], turning both Finlay and Hornswoggle [[Face (professional wrestling)|faces]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2007/matches/433496412|title=Friends The Great Khali def. Hornswoggle (DQ)|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> At [[Armageddon (2007)|Armageddon]], Finlay was placed in a match with Khali. Finlay scored an upset win after Hornswoggle interfered by hitting Khali in the groin with a [[shillelagh (club)|shillelagh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/2007/matches/5546604|title=Finlay def. The Great Khali|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Still battling Khali and his translator, Ranjin Singh, with Hornswoggle, he qualified for the [[Royal Rumble (2008)|Royal Rumble]]. He drew number 27, but was immediately disqualified when he entered before his time to save Hornswoggle. Hornswoggle, who was also a competitor in the Rumble, was disqualified as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/2008/matches/5267610321112|title=John Cena wins the Royal Rumble Match|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Finlay fought in the [[Elimination Chamber]] match at [[No Way Out (2008)|No Way Out]], ultimately being pinned after a [[chokeslam]] on the steel floor by [[The Undertaker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2008/02/18/4856515.html|title=Chamber matches dominate No Way Out|date=18 February 2008|last=Hillhouse|first=David|accessdate=14 October 2008|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref>\n\nFinlay then began making occasional appearances on ''Raw'' to protect Hornswoggle from [[Vince McMahon|Mr. McMahon]], who had been showing him \"tough love\". After Hornswoggle was [[Kayfabe|injured]] in a Steel Cage match by [[John Layfield|John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/02182008/|title=Outrage in a Cage|date=18 February 2008|last=Adkins|first=Greg|accessdate=29 February 2008|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Layfield revealed that Finlay was Hornswoggle's father, and not McMahon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/02252008/|title=The Truth about Hornswoggle, According to JBL|date=25 February 2008|last=Clayton|first=Corey|accessdate=16 March 2008|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> A week after, on 3 March, Finlay admitted to this fact.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/03032008/|title=Family Outrage|date=3 March 2008|last=Adkins|first=Greg|accessdate=16 March 2008|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> At [[WrestleMania XXIV]] he was defeated by Layfield in a [[No Disqualification match|Belfast Brawl]], where Hornswoggle also reappeared.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/24/matches/6515958|title=JBL def, Finlay in a Belfast brawl|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the [[2008 WWE draft#Supplemental draft|2008 WWE supplemental draft]], Finlay was drafted to the [[ECW (WWE brand)|ECW brand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/wwedraft2008/7505418/|title=Official 2008 WWE Supplemental Draft Results|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=25 June 2008}}</ref> He and Hornswoggle challenged [[The Miz]] [[John Morrison and The Miz|and]] [[John Morrison (wrestler)|John Morrison]] for the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Championship]] at [[Night of Champions (2008)|Night of Champions]], but lost. Throughout the rest of 2008, Finlay challenged for the [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship|ECW Championship]]. He, along with [[Matt Hardy]], [[Chavo Guerrero Jr.|Chavo Guerrero]], [[The Miz]] and ECW Champion [[Mark Henry]] participated in the first ever Championship Scramble match at [[Unforgiven (2008)|Unforgiven]] which Matt Hardy won.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/unforgiven/2008/7938432|title=Matt Hardy wins ECW Championship Scramble|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> He defeated Mark Henry on an episode of ''[[ECW (WWE)|ECW]]'' to earn an opportunity for the ECW championship, but was defeated by the champion Matt Hardy. Then he started a feud with Henry, and the feud ended when Finlay defeated Henry in a Belfast Brawl match at [[Armageddon (2008)|Armageddon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2008/12/14/7749336.html|title=Armageddon: Hardy finally breaks through|date=14 December 2008|last=Bishop|first=Matt|accessdate=2 April 2009|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref>\n\n==== Brand switches and departure (2009\u20132011) ====\nFinlay entered his third Royal Rumble match at the [[Royal Rumble (2009)|eponymous pay-per-view]] on 25 January 2009, where he entered at number 14 and lasted 30 minutes before being eliminated by Kane.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/2009/participants09/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091218020832/http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/2009/participants09|title=2009 Royal Rumble Eliminations and Statistics|publisher=WWE|archivedate=18 December 2009|accessdate=25 November 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> At [[No Way Out (2009)|No Way Out]], Finlay faced [[Jack Swagger]] for the ECW Championship in a losing effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/nowayout09/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090219192031/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/nowayout09/|url-status=dead|title=No Way Out 2009|accessdate=25 November 2018|archivedate=19 February 2009|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> On 13 March episode of ''SmackDown'', Finlay defeated [[The Brian Kendrick]] to qualify for the Money in the Bank ladder match at [[WrestleMania XXV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wwe/smackdown/_2009/_09031|title=SmackDown \u2014 March 13, 2009|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=25 November 2018}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> At the event, Finlay failed to win the match as it was won by CM Punk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/25/results|title=Full WrestleMania XXV results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> In the [[2009 WWE draft#Supplemental Draft|2009 Supplemental Draft]], Finlay and Hornswoggle were separated when Hornswoggle was drafted to Raw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2009draft/2009supplementaldraftresults/|title=2009 WWE Supplemental Draft results|date=15 April 2009|accessdate=15 April 2009|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> In late May 2009, Finlay suffered a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#legit|legitimate]] eye injury, sidelining him temporarily.<ref>https://bleacherreport.com/articles/286469-eying-down-an-irishman-a-look-at-the-career-of-finlay</ref> He returned on 16 June, attacking ECW Champion [[Tommy Dreamer]], [[Christian Cage|Christian]], and Jack Swagger. At [[WWE The Bash|The Bash]], he participated in a Championship Scramble match for the ECW Championship, which also included Christian, Jack Swagger and Mark Henry, however the defending champion Tommy Dreamer retained. Finlay did not return to ECW after that.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_33162.shtml|url-status=dead|archivedate=30 June 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630054308/https://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_33162.shtml|title=CALDWELL'S WWE THE BASH PPV REPORT 6/28: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of Orton vs. Triple H, Punk vs. Hardy|author=Caldwell, James|date=30 June 2009|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was traded to the SmackDown brand on 29 June 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/06292009/articles/10680372|title=Trump's Last Laugh|date=28 June 2009|accessdate=18 July 2009|publisher=[[WWE]]}}</ref> He went on to form part of [[John Morrison (wrestler)|John Morrison]]'s team at [[Survivor Series (2009)|Survivor Series]], but he was eliminated by [[Sheamus]], and his team eventually lost. In late 2009, he began pursuing the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]] by feuding with [[Drew McIntyre]], which he failed to win. His final televised match in WWE was on 4 June 2010 episode of ''SmackDown'' where he competed in a 15 man [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|battle royal]]. He failed to win as the match was won by former rival [[Rey Mysterio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wwe/smackdown/_2010/_100604/|title=SmackDown \u2014 June 4, 2010|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref> In 2010, Finlay more or less stepped away from the ring, becoming a full-time trainer and agent.\n\nFinlay was released in March 2011 after authorising the interruption of the American national anthem by [[The Miz]] during a house show, which offended many, including [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] members who were in attendance. Finlay stated that his intention was to intensify the audience's dislike of The Miz in preparation for the latter's [[WrestleMania XXVII]] main event appearance, but accepted full responsibility for his dismissal.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n=== Independent circuit and retirement (2011\u20132012) ===\n[[File:FinlayVersusSmith.jpg|thumb|Finlay wrestling [[Harry Smith (wrestler)|Harry Smith]] in November 2011]]\nAfter being released from WWE, Finlay was contacted by [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] several times, but was unable to agree upon contractual terms.{{cn|date=January 2020}} He began to wrestle again on the [[independent circuit]], making his first appearance on 26 July 2011, defeating [[Sami Callihan]] at [[Evolve (professional wrestling)|Evolve 9]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_51704.shtml|title=Radican's \"Evolve 9\" virtual time iPPV results 7/26: Finlay vs. Callihan, Taylor vs. Gargano main event|last=Radican|first=Sean|date=26 July 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 2011, Finlay made his debut for [[Pro Wrestling Guerrilla]], taking part in the [[Battle of Los Angeles (professional wrestling)#2011|2011 Battle of Los Angeles tournament]]. He was eliminated from the tournament in the first round by [[PWG World Championship|PWG World Champion]] [[Kevin Owens|Kevin Steen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_52395.shtml|title=8/20 PWG results in Reseda, Calif.: BOLA tournament winner, Young Bucks not shaking hands turned into angle, Tag Title match, Finlay debuts|last=Massingham|first=Matt|date=21 August 2011|accessdate=21 August 2011|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 October 2011, Finlay's debut for [[Yoshihiro Tajiri]]'s [[Smash (professional wrestling)|Smash]] promotion was announced, when he was revealed as the mysterious \"King of Terror\", Michael Kovac had promised to bring to the promotion and named first ever [[Smash Championship|Smash Champion]] [[Michael Majalahti|StarBuck]]'s first challenger for the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smashxsmash.jp/cgi-bin/result/diary.cgi?no=289|script-title=ja:\u521d\u4ee3\u738b\u8005\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30d0\u30c3\u30af\u304c\u30d5\u30a3\u30f3\u30ec\u30fc\u306b\u5ba3\u6226\u5e03\u544a\uff01|date=28 October 2011|accessdate=28 October 2011|work=[[Smash (professional wrestling)|Smash]]|language=Japanese|title=Smashxsmash.jp}}{{dead link|date=July 2012}}</ref> On 24 November at ''Smash.23'', Finlay defeated StarBuck to become the new Smash Champion.<ref name=Smash23>{{cite web|url=http://www.smashxsmash.jp/smash_archives/information/1124_smash23/smash23_5.html|title=\u300eSMASH.23\u300f\u8a66\u5408\u30ec\u30dd\u30fc\u30c8\uff08\u30e1\u30a4\u30f3\u30a4\u30d9\u30f3\u30c8\uff09|date=25 November 2011|accessdate=14 December 2011|work=[[Smash (professional wrestling)|Smash]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> On 19 February, Finlay made his first successful defence of the Smash Championship, defeating TAJIRI. Prior to the event, Smash had announced that it would cease its operations on 14 March, which led to Finlay vacating the Smash Championship after the title defence.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.smashxsmash.jp/smash_archives/information/smash25/smash25_allresult.html | title = 2\u30fb19\u300eSmash.25\u300f\u5168\u8a66\u5408\u7d50\u679c | date=19 February 2012 | accessdate=19 February 2012 | work=[[Smash (professional wrestling)|Smash]] | language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 November 2011, Finlay wrestled in the main event of a [[Stampede Wrestling]] show in [[Barrie, Ontario]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Gibson|first=Shawn|title=Wrestling hits the ANAF Club|url=http://www.simcoe.com/sports/sports/article/1236185|accessdate=19 January 2012|newspaper=Simcoe.com|date=2 November 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627230838/http://www.simcoe.com/sports-story/2068548-wrestling-hits-the-anaf-club/|url-status=dead|archivedate=27 June 2013}}</ref> in a losing effort against [[Harry Smith (wrestler)|Harry Smith]].\n\nOn 21 January 2012, Fit Finlay returned to DOA Pro Wrestling in Portland, OR to face [[Ethan HD]] for the DOA Heavyweight Championship.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nOn 12 May 2012, at [[Border Wars (2012 wrestling event)|Border Wars]], Finlay made his debut for [[Ring of Honor]] (ROH), unsuccessfully challenging [[Roderick Strong]] for the [[ROH World Television Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1336878002 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121205100723/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1336878002 |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 December 2012 |title=ROH Border Wars iPPV Results- 5/12/12 |last=Namako |first=Jason |date=12 May 2012 |accessdate=12 May 2012 |work=WrestleView }}</ref> On 24 May, Finlay made his debut for [[Wrestling New Classic]] (WNC), the follow-up promotion to Smash, defeating [[Akira Nogami|Akira]] in the main event.<ref name=WNCStartingOver>{{cite web|url=http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/fight/other/live/2012/2012052402/index.html |title=Wrestling New Classic\u300c\u65d7\u63da\u3052\u6226\u300d |date=24 May 2012 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |work=Sports Navi |publisher=[[Yahoo!]] |language=Japanese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527164325/http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/fight/other/live/2012/2012052402/index.html |archivedate=27 May 2012  }}</ref> Two days later, Finlay defeated Zeus in the main event of another WNC event. Finlay's first tour of WNC concluded on 27 May, when he, Akira and [[Syuri]] defeated [[Kana (wrestler)|Kana]], [[Mikey Whipwreck]] and Tajiri in a six-person main event. On 24 June at ROH's [[Best in the World 2012: Hostage Crisis]] iPPV, Finlay was defeated by [[Michael Elgin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/118-daily-updates/26253-roh-best-in-the-world-ippv-coverage-from-new-york|title=ROH Best in the World iPPV coverage from New York|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=24 June 2012|accessdate=24 June 2012|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref>\n\nFinlay returned to WNC on 20 September, when he defeated [[Villano V|Ray Mendoza, Jr.]] in the main event at [[Korakuen Hall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestling-newclassic.com/ja/329-2012-9-20-korakuen-result.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121205011121/http://wrestling-newclassic.com/ja/329-2012-9-20-korakuen-result.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 December 2012 |script-title=ja:\u7687\u5e1d\u5bfe\u6c7a\u306e\u884c\u65b9\u306f!? 9\u30fb20\u5f8c\u697d\u5712\u30db\u30fc\u30eb\u5927\u4f1a \u5168\u8a66\u5408\u7d50\u679c |date=20 September 2012 |accessdate=20 September 2012 |work=[[Wrestling New Classic]] |language=Japanese }}</ref> Following the match, Finlay announced that he was done with WNC for the time being due to re-signing with WWE.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://battle-news.com/battle/2012/09/001434.php | title = \u30e1\u30f3\u30c9\u30fc\u30b5Jr\u3068\u306e\u91cd\u539a\u304b\u3064\u30af\u30e9\u30b7\u30ab\u30eb\u306a\u4e00\u6226\u3092\u5236\u3057\u305f\u30d5\u30a3\u30f3\u30ec\u30fc\u304c\u3001\u5185\u6226\u771f\u3063\u53ea\u4e2d\u306eWNC\u306b\u30e1\u30c3\u30bb\u30fc\u30b8\uff01 |date=20 September 2012 | accessdate=20 September 2012 | work=Battle News | language=Japanese}}</ref> Despite no longer scheduled to make appearances for WNC, Finlay was named the head of the WNC Championship Committee.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://wrestling-newclassic.com/ja/news-navi/357-wnc-wnc.html | title = \u3064\u3044\u306b\u5230\u7740\uff01WNC\u738b\u5ea7\u3001WNC\u5973\u5b50\u738b\u5ea7\u306e\u30d9\u30eb\u30c8\u521d\u516c\u958b\uff01 | date = 20 October 2012 | accessdate = 25 October 2012 | work = [[Wrestling New Classic]] | language = Japanese }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Return to WWE (2012\u2013present)===\nFollowing a stint in the [[independent circuit]] and a year after the [[house show]] incident, Finlay returned on 11 July 2012 as a backstage producer. The two sides had been negotiating since [[WrestleMania XXVIII]], but there were situations that delayed the deal being finalised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twnpnews.com/2012/07/fit-finlay-returns-to-wwe-aw-comments-on-mitb-pre-show-match-retro-raw-t-shirts/|title=Fit Finlay Returns to WWE, AW Comments on MITB Pre-show Match, Retro RAW T-shirts \u00bb TWNP-Wrestling News|last=Middleton|date=11 July 2012|publisher=}}</ref> During the following years, Finlay made some [[cameo appearance]]s, usually separating wrestlers brawling between them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/pro-wrestling/ring-posts-blog/bal-wwe-stephanie-mcmahon-brie-bella-feud-raw-20140729-story.html|title=Stephanie McMahon-Brie Bella feud highlights RAW|last=Oster|first=Aaron|work=baltimoresun.com|access-date=9 June 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Also, he was one of the four wrestlers who presented [[Tyler Bate]] with the [[WWE United Kingdom Championship|WWE UK Championship]] after winning the related tournament in January 2017.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nAt the [[Royal Rumble (2019)|2019 Royal Rumble]], Finlay gave [[Becky Lynch]] the go-ahead to take the place of [[Lana (wrestler)|Lana]] in the women's Royal Rumble match after the latter was unable to compete following an attack by [[Nia Jax]] on the entrance way, which worsened her [[kayfabe]] ankle injury.{{cn|date=January 2020}} Lynch went on to win the match.\n\n== Other media ==\n=== Video games ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Notes\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[WCW/nWo Revenge]]''\n|Video game debut<br>as Fit Finlay\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2007]]''\n|As Finlay\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2008]]''\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2009]]''\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2010]]''\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2011]]''\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[WWE SuperCard]]''\n|Mobile game\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[WWE 2K15]]''\n|As [[downloadable content]]<br>as Fit Finlay\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[WWE 2K16]]''\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n== Personal life ==\nBoth Finlay's father, David Finlay Sr., and his grandfather were professional wrestlers, and his sister was a [[Referee (professional wrestling)|referee]]. His brother, Albert, was a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Glentoran FC]] in the 1960s and 1970s. Finlay was previously married to his former manager, Princess Paula.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> He is currently married to a German woman named Mel and has three children, the eldest of whom, [[David Finlay (wrestler)|David]], was born in Germany.<ref name=herald/>\n\nHis children are all [[amateur wrestlers|wrestlers]]. The oldest, [[David Finlay (wrestler)|David]], made his professional wrestling debut on 22 December 2012 and is now wrestling for [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling|New Japan Pro Wrestling]] (NJPW) and [[Ring of Honor]] (ROH). David is a former [[NEVER Openweight 6-Man Tag Team Championship|NEVER Openweight 6-Man Tag Team Champion]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=13926|title=\u300eSuper Jr.\u300f\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc\uff06\u5168\u30ab\u30fc\u30c9\u6c7a\u5b9a!\u3000\u5916\u9053\u304c3\u5e74\u3076\u308a\u51fa\u5834!\u3000\u30d5\u30a3\u30c3\u30b7\u30e5\u3001\u30aa\u30e9\u30a4\u30ea\u30fc\u3001\u5c0f\u677e\u3001\u30ab\u30d9\u30eb\u30ca\u30ea\u30aa\u3001\u30d5\u30a3\u30f3\u30ec\u30fc\u3089\u304c\u521d\u51fa\u5834!|date=7 May 2015|accessdate=7 May 2015|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling|New Japan Pro Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> His daughter has won the Georgia State championship.{{cn|date=January 2020}} The family resides in [[Atlanta]], Georgia.\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n* '''[[All Star Wrestling]]'''\n** [[British Heavyweight Championship#All Star Promotions|British Heavyweight Championship (1 time)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/uk/bri-h.html|title=British Heavyweight Title|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n* '''[[Catch Wrestling Association]]'''\n**[[CWA British Commonwealth Championship]] ([[CWA British Commonwealth Championship#Title history|1 time]])\n** [[CWA Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship]] ([[CWA Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/germany/cwa/cwa-ic-h.html|title=CWA Intercontinental Heavyweight Title (Austria / Germany)|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n** [[CWA World Middleweight Championship]] ([[CWA World Middleweight Championship#Title history|4 times]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/germany/cwa/eu-cwa-m.html|title=CWA World Middleweight Title (Austria / Germany)|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n** [[CWA World Tag Team Championship (Germany)|CWA World Tag Team Championship]] ([[CWA World Tag Team Championship (Germany)#Title history|1 time]])&nbsp;\u2013 with Marty Jones<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/germany/cwa/eu-cwa-t.html|title=CWA World Tag Team Championship history|publisher=titlehistories.com}}</ref>\n* '''''[[Fighting Spirit Magazine]]'''''\n** LL Cool J Award (2006)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestling.insidepulse.com/2007/08/01/69354/|title=Pulse Wrestling's Top 100 Wrestlers of the Modern Age: #77&nbsp;\u2013 Dave Finlay|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523075351/http://wrestling.insidepulse.com/2007/08/01/69354/|archivedate=23 May 2009}}</ref>\n* '''[[Professional wrestling in the United Kingdom#Joint Promotions|Joint Promotions]]'''\n** World Mid-Heavyweight Championship (4 times)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/eu-world-mh.html|title=World Mid-Heavyweight Title|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n** [[British Heavy Middleweight Championship]] ([[British Heavy Middleweight Championship#Title history|6 times]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/uk/bri-hm.html|title=British Heavy Middleweight Title|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n** [[British Light Heavyweight Championship]] ([[British Light Heavyweight Championship#Title history|2 times]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/uk/bri-lh.html|title=British Light Heavyweight Title|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n** ''[[World of Sport (UK TV programme)|World of Sport]]'' Top Tag Team Tournament 1982 (with [[Skull Murphy#Legacy|Skull Murphy (Peter Northey)]] as the Riot Squad.)<ref>http://itvwrestling.co.uk/82.html</ref><ref>''[[TV Times]]'' 27th November - 3rd December 1982, ITV listings for Saturday 27th November 1982, panel for ''[[World of Sport (UK TV programme)|World of Sport]]''</ref>\n* '''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n** Ranked No. 33 of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated#PWI 500|PWI 500]]'' in 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi50007.htm|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Top 500&nbsp;\u2013 2007|accessdate=10 March 2009|work=[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]|publisher=Wrestling Information Archive|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707054509/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi50007.htm|archivedate=7 July 2011 }}</ref>\n** Ranked No. 278 of the top 500 singles wrestlers of the \"PWI Years\" in 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi500yr.htm|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated's Top 500 Wrestlers of the PWI Years|accessdate=5 May 2008|work=[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]|publisher=Wrestling Information Archive|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707054220/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi500yr.htm|archivedate=7 July 2011 }}</ref>\n* '''[[Smash (professional wrestling)|Smash]]'''\n** [[Smash Championship]] ([[Smash Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=Smash23/>\n* '''[[World Championship Wrestling]]'''\n** [[WCW World Television Championship]] ([[List of WCW World Television Champions|1 time]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/tvwcw.html|title=Solie's Title Histories:WCW|website=www.solie.org|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n** Hardcore Junkyard Invitational Tournament (1999)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/hctwcw.html|title=Solie's Title Histories: WCW|website=www.solie.org|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n* '''[[WWE|World Wrestling Entertainment]]'''\n** [[WWE United States Championship]] ([[List of WWE United States Champions|1 time]])<ref name=US>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/unitedstates/244000611|accessdate=1 March 2009|title=Finlay's first WWE United States Championship reign|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603013005/http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/unitedstates/244000611|archivedate=3 June 2012}}</ref>\n** [[Bragging Rights (2009)|Bragging Rights Trophy (2009)]] \u2013 with [[Team SmackDown]] <small>([[Chris Jericho]], [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]], [[R-Truth]], [[Matt Hardy]], [[David Hart Smith]] and [[Tyson Kidd]])</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wwebraggingrights/2009|title=Bragging Rights 2009 results|website=[[WWE]].com|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.cultofwhatever.com/2012/04/dave-fit-finlay-interview/ Dave Finlay Interview]\n*{{wwe superstar|name = Finlay}}\n*{{twitter|ringfox1}}\n*{{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n{{Navboxes|\n|list1=\n{{CWA British Commonwealth Championship}}\n{{CWA Intercontinental Heavyweight Champions}}\n{{CWA World Middleweight Championship}}\n{{CWA World Tag Team Championship}}\n{{WWE United States Championship}}\n{{WCW World Television Championship}}\n{{WWE personnel}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finlay, Dave}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Expatriate sportspeople from Northern Ireland in the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male professional wrestlers from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:NWA/WCW World Television Champions]]\n[[Category:NWA/WCW/WWE United States Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:People from Carrickfergus]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling executives]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling managers and valets]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling trainers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Belfast]]\n[[Category:Ulster Scots people]]\n", "name_user": "Longdongwong", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dave_Finlay"}
{"title_page": "Fiddler Records", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=December 2010}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name = Fiddler Records\n| image = Fiddler white logo.jpg\n| caption = Fiddler Logo\n| background = group_or_band\n| origin = [[Miami]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| genre = {{flatlist| \n* [[Rock music|Rock]]\n* [[punk rock]]\n* [[experimental rock]]\n* [[emo]]\n* [[hardcore punk]]\n}}\n| years_active = 1996\u20132006\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist| \n* [[Dashboard Confessional]]\n* [[New Found Glory]]\n* [[The Bled]]\n* [[Recover (band)|Recover]]\n* [[The Higher]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|fiddlerrecords.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Fiddler Records''' was a small [[independent record label]] serving as the launch pad for several artists seminal to the [[Pop music|pop]], [[Punk rock|punk]] and [[emo]] genres.  Starting as the brainchild of 16-year-old entrepreneur Amy Fleisher Madden in 1996, the label became well known for its early releases from marquee artists [[Dashboard Confessional]] and [[New Found Glory]].  Over the course of 10 years, Fiddler Records developed a steady roster of successful artists such as [[The Bled]], [[The Higher]], [[Recover (band)|Recover]], [[Juliette & The Licks]], [[Name Taken]] and [[Classic Case]].\n\nCurrently, the Fiddler Records catalog is managed by Animal Manufacturing Co. Animal Manufacturing has released vinyl for both Recover and Name Taken and has helped keep the spirit of Fiddler alive.\n\n==History==\n\n===The Origin===\nFiddler Records started in 1996 by Amy Fleisher Madden at age 16.  What started as Amy passing out photocopies of her fanzine, Fiddler Jones, in the parking lot of Miami punk venue Cheers, became one of the most historic [[pop-punk]] labels of the late 1990s and early 2000s.\n\nAfter saving $600 from promoting several shows over the course of several months at Cheers, Amy invested the money in a 7\u201d by the band Vacant Andys (led by then unknown [[Chris Carrabba]] of [[Dashboard Confessional]]).  The gold vinyl release was titled ''Anodyne'', and marked the first release from both an artist and label showing signs of much bigger things on the horizon.\n\n===Getting Off The Ground===\nFiddler began building a roster with several records, including the label's forth release, [[New Found Glory]]'s ''[[It's All About the Girls]]'' (1997), which assisted the band in breaking nationwide. It eventually sold more than 80,000 copies, as New Found Glory went on to [[pop-punk]] stardom earning multiple gold records for major labels.  Fiddler began climbing the music industry ladder by signing to the Toledo, Ohio-based small distribution outfit Lumberjack Distribution, helping to develop some of the roster\u2019s core releases from such artists as [[Recover (band)|Recover]], The Agency, and The Gray AM.\n\nIn March 2000, Fiddler released ''[[The Swiss Army Romance]]'', a solo record from [[Chris Carrabba]]\u2019s solo project titled [[Dashboard Confessional]].  The record quickly garnered critical national acclaim, and within a few months the first pressing of CDs had sold out and Carrabba left his band [[Further Seems Forever]] to pursue Dashboard Confessional full-time. In order to meet the swelling demand, ''The Swiss Army Romance'' was sold from Fiddler to the [[MCA Records]] subsidiary [[Drive-Thru Records]].\n\n===15 Seconds===\nIn November 2002, Fiddler signed a label/distribution deal with [[MCA Records]].  In March 2003, MCA folded into [[Geffen Records]], which inherited Fiddler's contract.  While Fiddler\u2019s agreement with MCA kept them bound to Geffen, during the three years under this arrangement, the now fully staffed label released records from [[The Bled]] (who later went to [[Vagrant Records]]), [[The Higher]], Poulain, and Salem.\n\nIn 2005, Fiddler parted ways with Geffen and signed a distribution agreement with [[RED Distribution]], where they released records from [[Name Taken]], The Higher, [[Juliette & The Licks]] and a release from At All Cost under Fiddler\u2019s sub-label \u201cThe Imprint.\u201d\n\n===Winding Down===\nAfter many staff changes and band break-ups, Fiddler was dismantled in 2006.  Once again solely operated by Amy, Fiddler closed and left the label website with only the words \u201c''Gone fission' Fiddler no longer exists in the physical nor the metaphysical world.  Thanks for the postcards. We're all out of cats.''\u201d\n\n===Life After Death===\nIn late 2009, Amy started Animal Manufacturing Co, resurrected the historic label\u2019s catalog, remanifesting it back into the physical, metaphysical, and digital world once again, ensuring that the legacy of Fiddler lives on.\n\n==Discography==\n*FR001 - Vacant Andys - ''Anodyne'' (1996, 7\")\n*FR002 - The Skalidays - ''We Outgrew the Water Fountain'' (1996, 7\")\n*FR003 - The Skalidays - ''Late Again'' (1997)\n*FR004 - [[New Found Glory]] - \"It's All About The Girls\" - (1997, CDEP)\n*FR005 - Milkshed - \"Time\" (1997)\n*FR006 - The Agency - \"Fork, Knife and Spoon\" (1998, CDEP)\n*FR007 - Poopy Pants - \"Anal Devastation\" (1998, CDEP)\n*FR008 - Various Artists - \"The Shortest Distance: A South Florida Compilation\" (1999, CD)\n*FR009 - The Grey A.M. - \"Move the Monuments East (1999, CD)\n*FR010 - The Agency - \"Engines\" (2000)\n*FR011 - [[Dashboard Confessional]] - \"[[The Swiss Army Romance]]\" (2000, CD)\n*FR012 - [[Dashboard Confessional]] - [[The Drowning EP|The Drowning]] (2001, CDEP)\n*FR013 - [[Seville (band)|Seville]] - \"Waiting in Seville (2001, CDEP)\n*FR014 - [[Recover (band)|Recover]] - \"Ceci N'est Pas Recover\" (2002, CDEP)\n*FR015 - Poulain - \"For Passengers\" (2003, CDEP)\n*FR016 - [[The Bled]] - \"Pass the Flask\" (2003)\n*FR017 - [[The Higher]] - \"Star Is Dead\" (2004, CDEP)\n*FR018 - [[Salem (US band)|Salem]] - \"[[Love It or Leave Me]]\" (2003, CDEP)\n*FR019 - [[Name Taken]] - \"Hold On\" (2004, CD)\n*FR020 - [[Juliette & The Licks]] - \"[[...Like a Bolt of Lightning]]\" (2004, CDEP)\n*FR021 - [[The Higher]] - \"Histrionics\" (2005, CD)\n*FR022 - [[Juliette & The Licks]] - \"You're Speaking My Language\" (2005, CD)\n*FR023 -\n*FR024 - Maida - \"Renaissance In Reverse (2005, CD)\n*FR025 - [[Classic Case]] - \"Dress to Depress\" (2005)\n*IMP001 - At All Cost - \"Shattered Dreams and Bourgeois Schemes\" (2004, CDEP)\n*IMP002 - Maida - \"Remove the Funeral Attire\" (2004, CDEP)\n\nResources: \nhttp://www.browardpalmbeach.com/2003-04-03/news/sunshine-music-moguls/\n\nResources: \n[http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/2003-04-03/news/sunshine-music-moguls/ Sunshine Music Moguls (Broward New Times Article)]\n\n[http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/2001-08-23/music/chris-craft/ Chris Craft (Dashboard Confessional New Times Article)]\n\n[http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/2001-03-15/music/real-world-punk/ Real World Punk (New Found Glory New Times Article)]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fiddlerrecords.com/ Official Website]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/fiddlerrecords Fiddler MySpace Profile]\n*[http://www.facebook.com/fiddlerrecords Fiddler Facebook Profile]\n*[http://www.hellomynameisrecords.com Hello My Name Is Records Website]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/hellomynameisrecords Hello My Name Is Records MySpace Profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American record labels]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=December 2010}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name = Fiddler Records\n| image = Fiddler white logo.jpg\n| caption = Fiddler Logo\n| background = group_or_band\n| origin = [[Miami]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| genre = {{flatlist| \n* [[Rock music|Rock]]\n* [[punk rock]]\n* [[experimental rock]]\n* [[emo]]\n* [[hardcore punk]]\n}}\n| years_active = 1996\u20132006\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist| \n* [[Dashboard Confessional]]\n* [[New Found Glory]]\n* [[The Bled]]\n* [[Recover (band)|Recover]]\n* [[The Higher]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|fiddlerrecords.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Fiddler Records''' was a small [[independent record label]] serving as the launch pad for several artists seminal to the [[Pop music|pop]], [[Punk rock|punk]] and [[emo]] genres.  Starting as the brainchild of 16-year-old entrepreneur Amy Fleisher Madden in 1996, the label became well known for its early releases from marquee artists [[Dashboard Confessional]] and [[New Found Glory]].  Over the course of 10 years, Fiddler Records developed a steady roster of successful artists such as [[The Bled]], [[The Higher]], [[Recover (band)|Recover]], [[Juliette & The Licks]], [[Name Taken]] and [[Classic Case]].\n\nCurrently, the Fiddler Records catalog is managed by Animal Manufacturing Co. Animal Manufacturing has released vinyl for both Recover and Name Taken and has helped keep the spirit of Fiddler alive.\n\n==History==\n\n===The Origin===\nFiddler Records started in 1996 by Amy Fleisher Madden at age 16.  What started as Amy passing out photocopies of her fanzine, Fiddler Jones, in the parking lot of Miami punk venue Cheers, became one of the most historic [[pop-punk]] labels of the late 90\u2019s and early 00\u2019s.\n\nAfter saving $600 from promoting several shows over the course of several months at Cheers, Amy invested the money in a 7\u201d by the band Vacant Andys (led by then unknown [[Chris Carrabba]] of [[Dashboard Confessional]]).  The gold vinyl release was titled ''Anodyne'', and marked the first release from both an artist and label showing signs of much bigger things on the horizon.\n\n===Getting Off The Ground===\nFiddler began building a roster with several records, including the label's forth release, [[New Found Glory]]'s ''[[It's All About the Girls]]'' (1997), which assisted the band in breaking nationwide. It eventually sold more than 80,000 copies, as New Found Glory went on to [[pop-punk]] stardom earning multiple gold records for major labels.  Fiddler began climbing the music industry ladder by signing to the Toledo, Ohio-based small distribution outfit Lumberjack Distribution, helping to develop some of the roster\u2019s core releases from such artists as [[Recover (band)|Recover]], The Agency, and The Gray AM.\n\nIn March 2000, Fiddler released ''[[The Swiss Army Romance]]'', a solo record from [[Chris Carrabba]]\u2019s solo project titled [[Dashboard Confessional]].  The record quickly garnered critical national acclaim, and within a few months the first pressing of CDs had sold out and Carrabba left his band [[Further Seems Forever]] to pursue Dashboard Confessional full-time. In order to meet the swelling demand, ''The Swiss Army Romance'' was sold from Fiddler to the [[MCA Records]] subsidiary [[Drive-Thru Records]].\n\n===15 Seconds===\nIn November 2002, Fiddler signed a label/distribution deal with [[MCA Records]].  In March 2003, MCA folded into [[Geffen Records]], which inherited Fiddler's contract.  While Fiddler\u2019s agreement with MCA kept them bound to Geffen, during the three years under this arrangement, the now fully staffed label released records from [[The Bled]] (who later went to [[Vagrant Records]]), [[The Higher]], Poulain, and Salem.\n\nIn 2005, Fiddler parted ways with Geffen and signed a distribution agreement with [[RED Distribution]], where they released records from [[Name Taken]], The Higher, [[Juliette & The Licks]] and a release from At All Cost under Fiddler\u2019s sub-label \u201cThe Imprint.\u201d\n\n===Winding Down===\nAfter many staff changes and band break-ups, Fiddler was dismantled in 2006.  Once again solely operated by Amy, Fiddler closed and left the label website with only the words \u201c''Gone fission' Fiddler no longer exists in the physical nor the metaphysical world.  Thanks for the postcards. We're all out of cats.''\u201d\n\n===Life After Death===\nIn late 2009, Amy started Animal Manufacturing Co, resurrected the historic label\u2019s catalog, remanifesting it back into the physical, metaphysical, and digital world once again, ensuring that the legacy of Fiddler lives on.\n\n==Discography==\n*FR001 - Vacant Andys - ''Anodyne'' (1996, 7\")\n*FR002 - The Skalidays - ''We Outgrew the Water Fountain'' (1996, 7\")\n*FR003 - The Skalidays - ''Late Again'' (1997)\n*FR004 - [[New Found Glory]] - \"It's All About The Girls\" - (1997, CDEP)\n*FR005 - Milkshed - \"Time\" (1997)\n*FR006 - The Agency - \"Fork, Knife and Spoon\" (1998, CDEP)\n*FR007 - Poopy Pants - \"Anal Devastation\" (1998, CDEP)\n*FR008 - Various Artists - \"The Shortest Distance: A South Florida Compilation\" (1999, CD)\n*FR009 - The Grey A.M. - \"Move the Monuments East (1999, CD)\n*FR010 - The Agency - \"Engines\" (2000)\n*FR011 - [[Dashboard Confessional]] - \"[[The Swiss Army Romance]]\" (2000, CD)\n*FR012 - [[Dashboard Confessional]] - [[The Drowning EP|The Drowning]] (2001, CDEP)\n*FR013 - [[Seville (band)|Seville]] - \"Waiting in Seville (2001, CDEP)\n*FR014 - [[Recover (band)|Recover]] - \"Ceci N'est Pas Recover\" (2002, CDEP)\n*FR015 - Poulain - \"For Passengers\" (2003, CDEP)\n*FR016 - [[The Bled]] - \"Pass the Flask\" (2003)\n*FR017 - [[The Higher]] - \"Star Is Dead\" (2004, CDEP)\n*FR018 - [[Salem (US band)|Salem]] - \"[[Love It or Leave Me]]\" (2003, CDEP)\n*FR019 - [[Name Taken]] - \"Hold On\" (2004, CD)\n*FR020 - [[Juliette & The Licks]] - \"[[...Like a Bolt of Lightning]]\" (2004, CDEP)\n*FR021 - [[The Higher]] - \"Histrionics\" (2005, CD)\n*FR022 - [[Juliette & The Licks]] - \"You're Speaking My Language\" (2005, CD)\n*FR023 -\n*FR024 - Maida - \"Renaissance In Reverse (2005, CD)\n*FR025 - [[Classic Case]] - \"Dress to Depress\" (2005)\n*IMP001 - At All Cost - \"Shattered Dreams and Bourgeois Schemes\" (2004, CDEP)\n*IMP002 - Maida - \"Remove the Funeral Attire\" (2004, CDEP)\n\nResources: \nhttp://www.browardpalmbeach.com/2003-04-03/news/sunshine-music-moguls/\n\nResources: \n[http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/2003-04-03/news/sunshine-music-moguls/ Sunshine Music Moguls (Broward New Times Article)]\n\n[http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/2001-08-23/music/chris-craft/ Chris Craft (Dashboard Conf